At the end of the exchanges, the Prague stock exchange swung into the negative
After Tuesday morning's fall, the Prague Stock Exchange crushed its losses.
Trading with ČEZ shares reached almost half of the usual daily trading.
On Tuesday, as soon as trading began, the Prague stock exchange returned to its fall of the previous day, when it lost almost six percent.
This time, the decline is due to the fall in stocks on Wall Street.
The market's reaction to the result of the vote by the US House of Representatives, which refused to adopt the US financial sector stabilisation plan, is thus also visible in our country.
Falling equities in Asia
Asian stock markets experienced a dramatic fall on Tuesday, even if the indices managed, during the day, to erase some of the losses.
The Hang Seng Index of the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost four percent in trading, but later erased some of the losses and reduced the decline to nearly 2.5 percent.
The Hang Seng China Enterprises index tracking the movement of Chinese stocks on the Hong Kong Stock Exchange lost 3.8 percent as markets closed in Shanghai.
Sydney Stock Exchange shares lost more than five per cent, but eventually the losses were reduced to 4.3 per cent.
According to its index, the Taiwan Stock Exchange lost 3.6 percent.
"The hesitation about the US bailout will affect financial markets around the world," said Joseph Yam, head of Hong Kong's monetary board.
Although Hong Kong is part of China, it sets its own monetary policy, i.e. independently of the Chinese central bank.
Interest rates in Hong Kong are at the same level as in the United States.
According to Australian Prime Minister Kevin Rudd, US lawmakers should quickly resume negotiations and adopt the proposal to support the financial system.
Otherwise, there is a risk that other countries will be affected.
The bloodbath in U.S. equities
On Monday, the US House of Representatives rejected the plan to support the financial system, to which it should have spent up to 700 billion dollars (nearly 12 billion dollars).
The lawmakers thus reneged on President George Bush's call for support for President George Bush's project.
According to Bush, the project should address the main causes of the financial crisis and help stabilize the entire economy.
U.S. stocks were bloodbathed on Monday and major equity indexes fell by the most in 20 years.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average lost nearly seven percent, having last fallen on such a scale in 1987.
The index was already losing during the vote, but when it appeared that the proposal was not adopted, it was in free fall.
Congress caved in: U.S. government can pump $700 billion into banks
U.S. congressional leaders and President George W. Bush's administration have agreed on a broader form of the agreement to provide financial assistance to the U.S. financial system.
It will be put to a vote early next week.
U.S. lawmakers made a turning point in talks on the adoption of a bailout package in the form of $700 billion (about 12 trillion crowns) in financial aid to the U.S. financial system.
Success is not certain.
Indeed, before they can publish the final version of the law and put it to a vote, the Congressmen must complete a number of details of the agreement.
The plan to support the financial system will be discussed in the House of Representatives on Monday.
Barney Frank, chairman of the House Banking and Financial Regulation Committee, told Reuters on Sunday.
According to sources, on Wednesday at the earliest, the plan should a priori be submitted to the vote in the Senate.
According to economists, the announcement that the bailout will be adopted should be a first major psychological factor in reviving financial markets.
However, given the complexity of the mechanisms through which market support can be effective, there will be a "disillusionment".
Paulson: The plan must be effective
"We have made great progress.
We have settled our differing views on what form the market stabilization package should take," Democrat Nancy Pelosi told Bloomberg.
According to her, the final vote could be carried out as early as Sunday.
On the night of Saturday to Sunday, representatives of the legislators met with US Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, in order to give the substance of the government a final form.
The latter should buy back from financial companies the unsaleable real estate assets that are causing financial companies to make considerable losses and threatening the stability of the system as a whole.
"We are close to agreeing on a plan that will work and that must also be effective in the market.
We still need to continue this market recovery plan, but I think we're there," Paulson said.
A signal for Asian trade
The global financial crisis is having a significant impact on falling equity markets.
According to Democratic Senator Harry Reid, lawmakers are working for Congress to reach a final agreement as early as Sunday.
They want to calm investors before the start of trading in Asian financial markets, which are located in the first time zone, where the decision of Congress could affect Monday's trading.
However, for the moment, it is impossible to specify with certainty when the two houses of the US Congress will proceed to the vote, or whether the negotiations are not likely to remain blocked, at the last moment, by this or that problem.
Lawmakers hope it will be passed in the coming days.
Nevertheless, the law will still undergo many amendments.
The total amount intended for the aid of the system must be divided into two parts.
The first $350 billion, as President George Bush wanted, must be available as soon as possible.
But, if Congress feels that the program is not fulfilling its function, it has the option of blocking the remaining amount, following two steps: first an additional $100 billion, and then, finally, $350 billion.
Bush hailed progress in negotiations
While the president can veto this decision, Congress has the option of outvoting him.
Despite these changes, the main idea of the program, which was to obtain finance for the purchase of bad real estate titles, whose value plummeted, because hundreds of thousands of Americans are unable to pay their mortgages, was maintained.
"All the work is done.
The House of Representatives should be able to vote on the bill on Sunday, and the Senate on Monday," said Republican Senator Judd Gregg.
US President George Bush himself is pleased with the progress in the negotiations.
His spokesman Tony Fratto said Bush was pleased with Saturday's progress and appreciated "the bipartisan effort to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy."
Limitation of golden parachutes
Senate Banking Committee Chairman Christopher Dodd, chief negotiator, says lawmakers have agreed on responsibility for the fiscal program, protecting contributors from losses, agreeing to rebates, running the plan on the timeline.
The new law also provides for the limitation of so-called golden parachutes for directors of companies participating in the programme and establishes a committee, which will oversee the fund.
The latter should be managed by the Ministry of Finance.
"We've been working very this issue and have made significant progress toward a deal that will work and be effective for the market and for all Americans," Paulson said.
The plan also provides assistance for property owners, who have problems paying.
The government should negotiate new down payments for mortgages it will buy, while reducing debtors' monthly payments and allowing them to keep their homes.
Marek: Psychological help
According to David Marek, chief economist at Patria Finance, the proposed plan is a good idea, but it will be very difficult to implement.
"And this is due to the fact that it is unclear what the mechanism and price of buying the problem assets will be.
This will be decisive in deciding on the sharing of losses between the financial sector and the government," Marek told Server iHNed.cz this week.
Whether the plan will be adopted now, or early next week, is, according to Marek, not that important.
"It is much more important that the congressmen agree, as early as this week, that they support this plan and that they will enshrine it as soon as possible.
This psychological significance of the agreement, providing for the adoption of the plan, matters most at this time," Marek stressed.
Triumph of right-wing populists in Austria, they have 29 percent in total
According to preliminary results, the early parliamentary elections in Austria brought a significant weakening of the two parties forming the current grand coalition, as well as a notable strengthening of populist parties.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP), where the position of the present President Wilhelm Molterer is seriously threatened, suffered particularly heavy losses.
On the other hand the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the governor of Carinthia Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to the political scene at national level.
According to preliminary results, the Socialists (SPÖ) remain, with 29.8 percent of the vote, the country's leading political force, however, compared to the 2006 elections, they lost 5.5 percent of the vote.
The ÖVP, which with 25.6 percent lost nearly nine percent of the vote, finished even worse.
These are the worst results of the two major parties in the post-war period; Especially for the People's Party, which called the early elections, the result is literally catastrophic.
Even at the beginning of July, when the ÖVP left the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead over the SPÖ.
But voters visibly punished them for letting the government collapse.
From the first reactions to the results, speculation about the possible resignation of the party leader and the current Vice-Chancellor Wilhelm Molterer was pronounced.
Observers believe this could happen as early as Monday, during the extraordinary council of the party leadership.
Such a development would a priori facilitate the path towards the outcome of the election result that remains the most likely, namely the renewal of the SPÖ and ÖVP grand coalition.
Nevertheless, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Free (FPÖ) would have obtained 18 percent and BZÖ eleven percent of the vote - the Socialists at the same time expressed the fear of a repeat of 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (at the time, the FPÖ was still unified, it was in 2005 that the BZÖ separated) on a common government.  which even provoked sanctions from the European Union.
Haider, who has already declared that he is ready to collaborate with any party and that he plans to return to Vienna on the national political scene, is apparently banking on this development.
The last party to gain access to parliament was the Greens, but these lost slightly and fell from third to fifth among Austrian political parties.
Obviously, no other party crossed the four percent limit and entered parliament.
A fight taken to the extreme: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you, how to choose
While virtually all mobiles can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make phone calls.
It seems to be clear that it is better to buy only a phone.
Nevertheless, there are enough reasons to get an independent reader.
The choice depends entirely on the mode of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It would be absurd to buy for the house an expensive high-end gramophone to put the new album of Maxim Turbulenc.
On the one hand, such musical products are not released on vinyl records, and, from the point of view of quality, there is no objective reason for this to happen.
However, if there are piled vinyl records on your shelves, with art rock, jazz or blues, you probably dream of such a gramophone.
The same is true of music on the go, namely compressed music, to put it simply—music in MP3.
Here too, there are categories based on price and quality.
For one, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a reader, in the same way that a Pink Floyd fan would find it difficult to bear headphones bought for twenty crowns at the market.
These are two extremes, between which there is enough room for everyone.
The choice is wide.
Battery life is also decisive
Some high-end music players are capable of much more than just music playback, but these are functions unknown, of course, to most mobiles.
No device today is as universal as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, phone calls and sending SMS, it is able to play music and movies, record them, it has a camera of variable quality and can, for example, be used for navigation.
And if we take into account smartphones and communicators, you will have in your pocket a small computer.
Since no fridge knows how to grill meat and no television will take photographs, we are practically witnessing a miracle.
However, the universal nature of the mobile is not without drawbacks.
The more functions you use, the shorter the interval between reloads.
And reading music is one of the most important energy goinfres.
Are rare mobiles that are able to play music for ten to twelve hours, in most cases this figure is significantly lower.
In this respect, music players (especially the most rudimentary) are much more efficient.
In the case of cheap mobiles, count on them playing music for only a few hours.
If, in addition, you happen to call from time to time, get a second recharge for work to be sure - this is valid even for more expensive devices.
This problem will not arise for MP3 players, which are capable, following recharging, of continuous operation of at least 9 hours, including the least efficient ones.
Another problem arises while recording music in the mobile.
Unfortunately, a limited part of the devices has a universal USB connector, especially since not all of them can be directly connected to the computer, without special software.
You can, of course, record music directly to the memory card, but few card readers know how to do it without reduction, given the tiny dimensions of memory cards used in mobiles.
As far as drives are concerned, you do not need, with some exceptions (iPod), any software.
Simply fill, through the USB connector, the music device from the computer.
Most mobiles and players will create themselves a media library classified according to the name of the performer, the title of the album, the style, or according to the judgment of the user.
Some devices display only an index with a tree structure, like the Windows Explorer, others are capable of both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with operating system).
Readers are easier to handle, mobiles have more know-how
When choosing a specific device, pay particular attention to the life of the battery, the capacity of the memory, the quality and type of sound output and, of course, the ease of control.
If music is for you, essentially, a background noise and if during the day you will listen to it only for a limited time, for example by taking the tram, you just need any mobile playing MP3.
Virtually all mobiles today are capable of this.
You don't even have to pay too much attention to the music formats that the mobile or player is able to play.
All of them manage to play MP3s and the vast majority of the music that will reach you will have precisely this format.
It is one of the most popular formats and apart from it, the vast majority of devices can also play WMA format music.
AAC (format used by Apple and its iPods), meanwhile, is less common.
High-end mobiles also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Simply visit the corresponding operator's (or those of another provider's) website from your mobile phone and purchase the song or album in question.
This service alone should be a compelling reason to get a music mobile.
The operators' offer is unfortunately miserable and it is limited, in most cases, to radio tubes quickly made.
Prices are also not the lowest.
Nevertheless, it is generally considered that this way of buying music (whether by mobile phone, internet, or even wireless internet) will dominate the music industry in the future.
Most people always carry their mobile with them.
Every time you feel like listening to something, you just have to take the mobile out of your pocket, while you forgot your MP3 player at home.
However, it is also important if you always have headphones or a handsfree with connection.
If this is not the case, you can use the built-in speakers, which almost all mobiles have, but a minimum of MP3 players.
For many, the main advantage of music mobiles is their price.
The cheapest ones normally cost less than three thousand.
For a price of three four thousand crowns, one can have a walkman already very suitable.
However, in most cases, you will be limited by the lack of output for regular headphones.
The price of the best and best equipped phones, also provided with an input for ordinary headphones, does not exceed fifteen thousand.
Readers, on the other hand, have the advantage of having an easy order.
Really anyone manages to order the most rudimentary readers - which do not necessarily correspond to the cheapest (see our choice).
A minimum of functions; and the resemblance of the command to that of a cassette station, commonly used in the past, or a gramophone, is obvious.
There is no risk of collision in the form of mobile internet plugged in by chance, followed by a huge data transmission bill.
Which device to choose
Even the cheapest mobiles (e.g. The Vodafone 527) usually has a swappable memory card slot (the M2 type, microSD, and so on).
Even taking into account the additional purchase of such a card, you will not exceed two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
Basic models in principle only support cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB.
Only the most expensive get by even with 8 GB memory cards.
If you already own a mobile and still want to buy a cheap MP3 player, take a Cowon, a Creative, a Sony, a Samsung, an Emgeton, or an iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you should not spend more than 1,100 crowns.
If you are one of the most demanding listeners, choose specialized walkman mobiles (Sony Ericsson, some Nokia and Samsung).
These devices are equipped with independent control keys for MP3, and this is how the ease of control is closer to that of an independent MP3 player.
Sony Ericsson, whose mobiles in the walkman series have the same user menu as MP3 players sold separately, is the one that has gone the furthest in this area.
The same service, in the same price category, but with a longer memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (normally 15 hours, up to 35 hours), is provided by an MP3 player produced by one of the brands mentioned above.
A first virtual operator will reach the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe
The mobile market in Czechia is relatively advanced, with our operators offering virtually the same services as their partners in Western Europe.
Despite this, we still lack something - a virtual operator, which would force traditional operators to lower prices.
It may not be missing for a long time.
We have already mentioned many times on Mobil.cz the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
The ČTÚ (Czech Telecommunications Office), which reported that the price of an SMS was higher here than in the rest of the Union, confirmed this.
Thus, following the latest steps taken by the European Commission in the field of roaming fee regulation, a paradoxical situation is likely to arise - SMS sent from abroad will be cheaper for some customers of Czech mobile operators than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are keeping up so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, it lacks a competition that would really like to enter the fight.
This may seem paradoxical, given that we still have three mobile networks and a penetration that is well over 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
In this, Pavel Dvořák, the President of the Council of the Czech Telecommunications Office (ČTÚ), who has repeatedly stated that in the Czech Republic there is no room for another operator, is chordding with the operators.
It is probably true that a traditional operator with its own network apparently no longer has much luck (moreover, by the way, it would now find frequencies with difficulty).
However, there is still one possibility - a virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that led to a considerable drop in prices, to which traditional operators subsequently also had to react.
Yet, even before spoilers such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the market, voices similar to those we hear today in Britain were being heard.
However, it appeared that there was still room for such operators and that they could have real success.
We do not have to look too far to find examples.
In February we informed you of the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, this operator managed to gain more than 100 thousand customers and become the fifth operator in the country.
Let us add that behind the Mobilking, there is the financial group Penta, which owns among others the U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on a much more concrete target group.
For their operation to be effective, they need far fewer customers than a traditional operator.
They are exempt from the relatively high costs of building, operating and maintaining the mobile network.
Thus, around the world, virtual operators are profiling themselves as low-cost operators – they offer cheap calls and texts, which is often offset by a limited service offering.
For example, Tesco Mobile offers SMS in Great Britain at least half as expensive as its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, focusing on an unusual target group can also be a good publicity stunt.
Indeed, this operator specifically targets men.
"Real men choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust," says David Seibert, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates the virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept would be likely to work here as well.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav Čepický doubts: "The Czech market is relatively small for a segmental approach, on which most virtual operators are based.
Especially since it is relatively saturated from the point of view of service offering."
In Czechia, no chance, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are discussing the expansion of this successful project, but in Czechia the negotiations are not very promising.
The launch of Mobilking will instead take place in other countries in our area," Jana Studničková, spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone interview for Mobil.cz.
It thus indirectly confirmed that the operators in the Czech Republic were, in any event, not in favour of that idea.
On the contrary, they try to do everything possible so that a potential competitor cannot appear.
The GTS Novera group, which would like to take a new step to become a real competitor of Telefonika in the field of corporate customers, has not hidden, for quite some time, its intention to launch a virtual mobile operator.
"We are very keen to be able to offer our customers not only fixed telecommunications services, but also mobile ones.
And the sooner the better.
We have already negotiated this possibility on several occasions with all Czech mobile operators.
With some, we managed to move forward in the negotiations," said group spokesman Pavel Kaidl.
So the future may be bright.
According to unofficial information, it seems that we could perhaps welcome the first virtual operator already by the end of the year.
But for now, its creation is accompanied by total silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room in the Czech market for a virtual operator as such.
The Czech market is in comparison with others very specific.
For the moment, no subject with a complex and serious project in this field has contacted us," Vlastimil Sršeň of Telefonika O2's press department said in his statement to Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokeswoman Martina Kemrová says in a rare agreement with O2's statement: "We have not yet registered any viable and bilaterally advantageous project that could serve as a basis."
She added: "It is virtually out of the question that a virtual operator will appear in the T-Mobile network by the end of the year.
To operate in such a short period of time, we should have a concrete agreement now."
Instead, Vodafone is focusing its attention on fulfilling requests for its own 3G license.
Miroslav Čepický says of this: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of shared costs and infrastructure.
This is what we think means the most input from a customer perspective.
Vodafone's main strategy in this area is to find a partner to set up a common network for fast mobile internet."
Responsible authorities: in tune with operators
The approach of mobile operators is easily understandable, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would have led to a decrease in prices and therefore to a decrease in their profit.
What is the point of facilitating the advent of such a competitor?
When it comes to their interests, operators know how to get along like thieves at a fair. The quarrel accompanying the creation of the U:fon also testifies to this.
The greatest apparent pressure on ČTÚ, when U:fon was created, was that exerted by the company T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the ČTÚ web pages.
However, today, the U:fon lends itself to serve as an argument for not accepting a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová noted: "Competition in the mobile market has also recently been amplified by the entry of a fourth mobile operator.
Given the nature of the mobile RT market, it is obvious that the entry of an additional player would place high demands on it, and especially its services."
But given the attitude of the following mobile operators, the indifference of the Czech regulators seems disconcerting.
However, this is not just the attitude of the ČTÚ, which, unlike Great Britain and other developed countries, unfortunately does not have the power in the Czech Republic to intervene in economic competition.
It belongs exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Economic Competition (ÚOHS).
However, the latter adopted, in the face of this problem, its typical position.
"The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible following the conclusion of an agreement between a mobile operator and the virtual operator in question concerning the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such agreement has been concluded for the moment, because the offer of potential interested parties has not a priori been of sufficient interest to traditional operators," Kristián Chalupa of the ÚOHS External Relations Department said in response to our question.
A statement made in this way would not come as a surprise from representatives of the operators.
But on the part of an office, which must represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, also take care that no one takes advantage of its position on the market, such a statement is more than confusing.
Especially since Kristián Chalupa adds: "Abroad, where virtual operators are normally present, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to a decrease in the prices of mobile telephone services."
However, pushing for the honest functioning of the market and lower prices is apparently not in the interests of the ÚOHS.
What is indeed shocking is the almost touching concord of the three mobile operators, which stems from their reactions.
The question, if this is really a coincidence, arises quite naturally.
In the same way, a strictly identical price of gasoline at all service stations is probably due to chance and the hard fight of the competition.
"The Office has not found any evidence of anti-competitive behaviour in this regard, so it has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position, and therefore none has a correspondingly increased responsibility for its behaviour on the market.
The tools needed to open up the mobile market to virtual operators are probably even lacking in the telecommunications regulator," Chaloupa said in his statement.
The interpretation of market dominance is one of the many points of contention.
Of course, there is an analysis of the relevant markets prepared by the ČTÚ, according to which telecommunications constitute, from the point of view of economic competition, a single market.
None of the Czech operators has a dominant position on such a market.
However, some legal experts propose a different view of things: for the creation of a virtual operator to be possible, the consent of the network operator must be obtained each time.
And the mobile operator quite logically has the monopoly on its network.
This is how it necessarily plays a dominant role in a certain segment of its activity.
However, even without admitting this argument, it should at least be worrying for the ÚOHS that three mobile operators are visibly proceeding in a similar way.
However, the complaints of many interested parties (including GTS Novera, already mentioned) show that they face similar constraints in negotiations with all operators.
Shifting responsibility onto the ČTÚ is a fairly common trick in communications, by means of which the ÚOHS washes its hands of the case.
We have already encountered this type of attitude in several similar cases.
Unfortunately, the novelization of the recently adopted Telecommunications Act did not include an extension of the powers of the ČTÚ in the field of economic competition in telecommunications, although many specialists promised an improvement in the situation.
The representatives of the ÚOHS must know this very well, but their interests apparently lie elsewhere.
When no one is looking, it can work
That said, the operation of a kind of pseudo-virtual operators, several in Czech mobile networks, remains unnoticed.
These are companies that publish their own price lists for mobile telephone services, but these are only partially public.
In most cases, it is a question of firms dealing with multi-level marketing.
Particularized mobile telephone services are offered for example by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The price lists of these firms usually only reach elected officials.
The magic trick consists in the fact that the company does in front of the operator figure of a classic corporate customer, who orders a large quantity of SIM cards.
As an important customer, it obtains special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the commercial conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit such resale.
"If what you mention happens, it could be a breach of the contractual conditions that we would examine and that could lead to a cessation of collaboration with the company in question," Martina Kemrová replied to our question about this problem.
Nevertheless, it is quite unlikely that an echo of such activity has not reached the managers of mobile operators.
Especially in the case of the three companies mentioned, it can be thousands of customers.
No operator, however, is against such a procedure.
Indeed, the activities of these firms bring them non-negligible profits, and, at the same time, as opposed to real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav Čepický points out the possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of these companies are only used by a negligible percentage of customers.
In addition, they are forced to admit that the SIM card in their phone is not registered under their name, so they cannot fully dispose of it, like ordinary mobile operator customers."
This is precisely what should seem strange to ČTÚ.
In addition, another question arises at ÚOHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to such a procedure, why are they blocking the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the ÚOHS has relatively broad powers to be able to disclose such an activity, and if it will not wish to be satisfied with the explanations of the operators, who claim to have no idea that this would happen, their contractual conditions prohibiting it.
When we will no longer be the most expensive country
As we have already mentioned several times, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a considerable decrease in the price of services.
However, in practically all the countries where virtual operators appeared, the traditional operators tried, sometimes more, sometimes less, to prevent their creation.
The arguments used by the latter were practically the same - a market that was too small or even too saturated, problems with the quality of services, etc.
However, it is precisely at this level that regulatory bodies in developed countries have intervened, which defended not the interests of mobile operators, but those of their customers.
Both through formal measures and informal pressure, they eventually obtained the creation of a first virtual operator, followed by others.
Unfortunately, Czech regulators treat this issue like a hot potato that is disposed of by passing it on to a nearby target.
As a result of the experiences we have, we cannot get rid of the impression that confusion in skills is more than beneficial to them in these cases.
But let's not throw the handle after the knock.
If the behind-the-scenes information is true and a virtual operator will soon appear here, the Czech mobile market may get moving again.
If one of the operators has agreed to the creation of a mobile virtual operator, the ÚOHS will hardly be able to remain impassive in the face of the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And perhaps we will stop calling for more than in the rest of Europe.
The new Czech anthem has four new versions.
Choose the best one
Listen to the four achievements of the new version of the Czech national anthem.
On Sunday, on the occasion of Czech Nationality Day, Prime Minister Mirek Topolánek solemnly presented the new recordings of the national anthem Kde domov můj (Where is my homeland?).
The anthem was again recorded by the National Theatre Orchestra under the direction of Jiří Bělohlávek.
We have four versions - with male or female solo singing, choir performance and instrumental version.
Vocals are provided by Kateřina Kněžínková and Adam Plachetka.
Otakar Jeremiáš and Jaroslav Krček are the authors of the arrangements of the anthem.
You can listen to the four new versions on the iHNed.cz server.
Bělohlávek considers Czech national singing to be one of the most beautiful anthems.
As he had previously told Český rozhlas (Czech public radio), he chose solo versions of singers with young and representative voices, which are marked and appreciated, for the interpretation.
"From the beginning, I tried to make sure that both singers, as well as the choir, had good diction, so that we understood the lyrics, that they sang simultaneously," he said.
The Czech national anthem will celebrate its 175th anniversary next year.
The song Kde domov můj resounded for the first time in 1834 on the stage of Stavovské divadlo (Estates Theatre) in Fidlovačka (Kermesse des savetiers), an original Czech play by Josef Kajetán Tyl, accompanied by music by František Škroup.
It became popular and people spontaneously appropriated it.
After the creation of Czechoslaovaquie in 1918, the first verse naturally became part of the national anthem.
It remained one of the seven national symbols even after the creation of the independent Czech Republic.
