Prague public transport (MHD) will introduce chip into its ticketing system on Wednesday
Wednesday, 1 October 2008, the Pražský Dopravní podnik (Prague Transport Agency) will go down in history as the date on which the first passengers will board the metro, trams and buses, who, instead of having a paper ticket, will have an electronic coupon in their pocket.
At the moment, the latter is accessible to about one hundred thousand people, owners of the Opencard smart card.
Passengers can purchase a 30-day or 90-day voucher (it will be valid from 1 January 2009) and have it registered on their smart card at information points and offices of the Dopravní podnik (Transport Agency), located in the metro stations Muzeum, Můstek, Nádraží Holešovice, Anděl,  Roztyly, Letňany, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Kačerov and Luka.
From yesterday there is also the possibility to buy the coupons online on the web pages of the Dopravní podnik: www.dpp.cz.
More than four hundred people enjoyed the service during the morning.
Those who start using the online store can permanently forget about the ticket offices in metro stations, where until now they had to trample impatiently in long queues in order to get paper tickets.
Indeed, they will buy their voucher online and it will be registered on their Opencard in one of the thirteen Městská knihovna (municipal libraries).
"In these contact points, there is a counter available to passengers with trained staff, which will help interested parties with the purchase via the internet and, in addition, will record the coupon they have purchased on their card," says project spokesman Martin Opatrný.
In addition to the libraries, it will also be possible to save electronic coupons on the Opencard in vending machines installed in the vestibule of several metro stations.
What do these distributors look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket composting machines and passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Budějovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"Today the city has five, but by the end of the year there should be eighty," Opatrný added.
A vending machine will control the coupon instead of the driver
The PLCs that will work from tomorrow are easy to use.
Simply introduce the Opencard chip card and the previously purchased coupon will register itself on the card.
The electronic coupons are valid from tomorrow not only in the capital, but also in the vicinity of the city.
Namely in suburban trains and bus lines 300 to 499, which mainly use the inhabitants of the municipalities of Central Bohemia to access the capital.
"In trains integrated into Pražská integrovaná doprava (Integrated Transport of Prague), controllers are equipped with card readers, with the help of which they establish the temporary and zonal validity of coupons;" explained ticket control Filip Drápal of the Ropid organization, which designs Prague public transport timetables.
Suburban buses are equipped with card readers integrated into the driver's checkout.
When boarding it is therefore necessary not only to show the smart card to the driver, but also to place the Opencard in the indicated place on the side of the cash register.
This is how the driver checks the validity of the registered coupons.
"In case the passenger needs to check the validity of the registered coupons, there is nothing simpler than asking the driver for this information," Drápal added.
Passengers who do not take suburban buses and will not remember when the validity of their coupon expires, can rejoin the vending machines, initially used to save coupons on the card.
It is there, on the screen of the device, that the information concerning the validity of their document will be displayed.
The Sudetenland demanded a referendum in the USA
The Sudeten Germans demanded in 1945 that Šumava be integrated into the United States.
This stems from a letter deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna (The Scientific Library of South Bohemia).
If we cannot be part of Germany or Austria, we at least want to live under the patronage of the United States of America.
In 1945, some groups of Sudeten Germans allegedly addressed the President of the United States with such desire.
This stems, among other things, from a letter preserved in a private archive, which is now deposited in the collections of the Jihočeská vědecká knihovna.
Germans in Český Krumlov ask the US president in the letter not to allow "šumavská župa" (forest region in southern Bohemia) - annexed by Hitler under the Munich Agreement - to be returned to Czechoslovakia.
"We have understood the situation and want to be really sure that the words proclaiming that American troops come to German territory not as oppressors and enemies, but as liberators," reads the letter, signed "People, to whom the fate of Šumava is dear."
Since the rallying to Czechoslovakia is supposedly promising - knowing the Czech national character - only of brutality, inconsiderate attitude, misunderstanding, oppression and servitude, the authors of the letter ask the American President to take the protectorate of Šumava into his hands for now and forever.
"We cannot believe that you would grant this territory to a state foreign to us, which oppresses and destroys minorities and which did nothing to contribute to the victory of the Allies without taking into consideration the opinion of the quarter of a million inhabitants," the letter reads.
The alleged reason why the authors cannot sign the letter is fear of the desire for revenge of the "Czech oppressors".
If the President of the United States doubted the opinion of the Germans in Šumava, he would only have to organize, according to the authors of the letter, a referendum in the region to establish whether its inhabitants wanted to be part of the USA, or to live under the patronage of the United States.
Although the text contained in the letter may, given current knowledge of post-war history, seem somewhat naïve, according to some survivors, it illustrates well the expectations of the Sudeten Germans of the time.
While the Czech Germans must at least have foreseen that the question of their expulsion from the republic would arise, very few of them admitted such a possibility.
Some expected that the United States and Great Britain would obtain some kind of autonomy for the Sudetenland.
Others believed they would simply stay in Czechoslovakia.
The famous Austrian journalist Gustav Chalupa, born in České Budějovice, confirms this.
During the war, as a German from České Budějovice, he was engaged in the navy in the Baltic countries.
When at the end of the war he was captured by the British and placed in the capture camp in the Holstein region, dozens of Czech Germans came to consult him to teach them Czech.
"They believed that once they got home, Czech would benefit them," Chalupa said.
None of the captured Germans who lived in Czechoslovakia before the war believed, according to him, that, as a result of the Beneš Decrees, he would be expelled from the republic.
You don't think - you pay!
Emotional campaign will attack drivers
The most costly road safety action in Czech history.
A way to characterize the emotional media campaign that the Ministry of Transport intends to launch on Wednesday.
The office of Minister Aleš Řebíček believes that it will discourage drivers from dangerous driving behaviour.
This campaign costing 150 million will appear on television, radio, cinema, on the internet, but also on leaflets.
It should discourage drivers from driving fast and drinking and driving.
But also remind them to take the belt before starting.
Above all, it wants to touch the conscience of young drivers, motorcyclists, pedestrians, not to mention professional drivers.
What will appear in the spots?
Especially personal stories that will attack emotions.
This is also evidenced by the "bloody" slogan of the entire campaign:
You don't think - you pay!
The phrase "You don't think" is written in capital letters on the license plate.
Then, in a puddle of blood, there is the phrase "You will pay".
This must symbolize that we can pay with life for a moment of inattention.
The spots will "haunt" spectators until 2010.
The ministry was inspired by similar campaigns in Anglo-Saxon countries, where one can commonly see images with drastic images of the victims of accidents.
He believes that this will lead to a decrease in the accident rate and the number of deaths on Czech roads.
The spots were prepared by the Euro RSCG agency.
The strategy of sugar and whipping against drivers
"What works with drivers is the sugar and whip system.
For them, sugar is represented, for example, by saving time, when they run a red light.
The whip is the threat of a fine or an accident.
Drivers need to be reminded of the risks," says Martin Kořán, transport psychologist at Na Homolce Hospital.
This is why we need information campaigns in the press and especially negative advertising, says the psychologist.
Signs warning the danger to drivers are, according to him, already less effective.
"When a static hazard warning sign is installed, it will probably quickly merge with the environment and drivers will no longer notice it," Kořán said.
Olmert would return almost all the occupied territories in exchange for peace
Ehud Olmert, the president of Israel's interim government, came out in favor of returning virtually all the territories occupied in 1967, including the West Bank, East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, in exchange for peace with Palestine and Syria.
He made the statement in an interview published Monday by the Yedioth Ahronoth daily.
"We have to reach an agreement with the Palestinians, which means that it will be necessary to return almost all (occupied) territories, if not all," Olmert told the daily.
"We will keep a certain percentage of the territory, but we will have to cede to the Palestinians a similar percentage (of Israeli territory), because without it, peace will not be achieved," he added.
He admitted that the possible restitution would include East Jerusalem.
"Whoever desires security in Jerusalem, and especially does not want tractors and bulldozers to crush his feet, as happened to one of my best friends, will have to give up parts of Jerusalem," Olmert remarked, referring to the two attacks in the city in July, in which several people were killed and dozens injured.
According to the prime minister, it will be necessary to find "a special solution for the Temple Mount, the sacred and historical places" located inside the Old City.
"Whoever wants to maintain Israeli sovereignty over the entire city will be forced to integrate 270,000 Arabs.
It won't work," he later stressed.
Golan Heights retreat
Olmert also spoke in favour of Israel's retreat from the Golan Heights, which he said was a prerequisite for a peace agreement with Syria.
However, this would also require some efforts on the part of Damascus.
"I am not proposing to conclude peace with Syria solely on the basis of a retreat from the Golan," he said.
"The Syrians know very well what they will have to give up to get the Golan.
They will have to give up their current relationship with Iran; they will have to renounce their relationship with Hezbollah (Shiite movement); they will have to renounce their constant support for the terrorism of Hamas (Shiite movement), al-Kaeda (terrorist network), as well as that of Jihad (holy war) in Iraq," the prime minister said.
Schwarzenberg: Relations with India are likely to cool
If the problem of Czech researchers accused of illegal cockroach picking could not be resolved, Czech Foreign Minister Karel Schwarzenberg would lead to a certain cooling of Czech-Indian relations.
The Minister said so today in New York, after meeting with his Indian counterpart Pranab Mukherjee.
"If the problem was not solved, then yes, some cooling would occur," he said after the meeting, which followed a Czech initiative.
Mukherjee said, as he left the talks, that it was difficult for the executive branch to intervene in court cases.
He mentioned, however, that in the case of Petr Švácha, who was cleared of the charge and punished with a fine, the central government could negotiate with the local government, that of Darjeling, the case being under the jurisdiction of the latter.
"His problem could be solved," the minister said.
According to Mukherjee, the best solution for Emil Kučera, who has been sentenced to three years in prison, would be to appeal to a higher court.
He could then apply for bail and await trial, he said.
Schwarzenberg confirmed that his partner also spoke in the same direction during the talks.
"He advises to appeal to a higher court, after which he could be pardoned," said the head of Czech diplomacy.
The only way the Czech side can intervene in this case is to provide the convicts with "competent legal support," the Indian minister said.
He also said that such assistance was already being provided to them by India as well.
"Above all, we want to maintain the best relations with India, which have a tradition that continues for many years.
The Indians recognize this as well," Schwarzenberg said.
At the same time, as he told ČTK, he stressed to his partner that the Czech Republic attaches great importance to the problem of Czech entomologies.
"We consider the incarceration and accusation of these Czech researchers to be a great misunderstanding," he said.
The minister dodged the question whether he had obtained a promise from India to deal with the matter.
"I've already received quite a few promises," he said only.
Questions that arise after the accident: Are the stewards on the bus illegal?
The law ignores them; Walking in a long-distance bus is prohibited
In the context of the tragic accident on the Student Agency bus near Padua, Italy, the question arises as to whether stewards and passengers can travel inside the coach during the journey.
"If one wanted to comply strictly and formally with the law, the activity of a steward is contrary to the law on road traffic," said transport ministry spokesman Karel Hanzelka.
The accident in question, in which a 22-year-old flight attendant perished, was apparently caused by the driver of a truck who crossed the path of the bus.
The girl was at that time unfortunately sitting next to the driver, in the most dangerous seat of the vehicle, although she had at her disposal two other seats.
However, the bus can have an accident, or even brake suddenly, also when the steward is serving coffee or distributing newspapers.
What matters is whether the coach is equipped with standing or not according to its data sheet.
If this standing equipment is not homologated, passengers must remain seated.
Student Agency long-distance coaches do not have standing room; this was confirmed to Aktuálně.cz by the company's director Radim Jančura.
"This is an issue we have dealt with with the ministry and, at first, it prohibits all passenger movement.
Then they cancelled it and we got passengers to go to the toilet during the journey as long as they have their own seat," he said.
The law ignores the steward
"There is no unequivocal legal interpretation of the role of steward - there is no legal requirement dealing with this role.
On the other hand, there is also no legal requirement that prevents the carrier from offering services.
The Road Transport Act only covers the term "vehicle receiver"; it does not define its rights and duties," Hanzelka spokesman added more ambiguously.
Josef Pokorný, director of the Department of Road Traffic, believes, on the contrary, that the law sufficiently addresses the problem.
"It all depends on whether the coach has permission in its homologation to offer standing places.
It's all in there," he said.
Coaches are divided into urban, where there are standing places and limited maximum speed, intercity with standing places and a higher authorized speed and long-distance coaches without standing with the highest maximum authorized speed and seats equipped with seat belts.
Like on the plane, says an expert
Jaroslav Hořín, an expert in transport safety at BESIP (Road Traffic Safety), does not see the movement of stewards on board as a major problem.
"In regular traffic, there is no danger. The situation can be compared to that of service on airplanes.
Again, it is not sure when turbulence will occur and the stewardess may hit her head."
"However, in the event that the bus braked suddenly, the laws of physics would obviously be valid.
In the same way as in a city bus or on a tram.
The carrier must manage the safety of stewards through internal regulations," he says and also believes that from the point of view of the law, the problem is not solved.
Jančura is ready to remove these services
Student Agency is the only coach carrier to offer stewards.
He hired two hundred.
Even after this accident, the manager does not consider their job to be a risky job.
"Nevertheless, as soon as I have the impression that this is a risky profession, I will delete it.
Passengers can receive their coffee and newspaper upon boarding.
It would also lower costs," he said.
Safety concerns are the reason given to the absence of stewards in his vehicles by the director of the Asiana Alexey Litvin, who ensures, in comparison with SA, a very small number of lines.
"We don't have hostesses. We have opposed it from the beginning.
Sooner or later it will end in a fatal accident," he told Týden.cz a year ago.
A huge tragedy has happened
A young hostess from the Plzeň region, who had been working for the company for two years, perished in the accident on the Naples line.
A Slovenian truck probably left the emergency lane without using a turn signal and blocked the way for the bus.
The latter's driver tried to avoid him by means of a sudden maneuver, but he brushed him by his right side.
Jančura refused that the two seats reserved for the rest of the stewards had been sold.
"In the case of long-distance lines, it is not possible to reserve these seats, they are blocked."
The company intends to file a complaint against the driver of the truck.
For the compensation of the girl's family, the agency will not wait for the judgment of the court, but as far as financial compensation is concerned, it also relies on the culprit.
A change in the law?
Not in sight
An amendment to the law, which has been being drafted for more than a year by a group of thirty experts from the Ministry of Transport, could clarify the movements of stewards on board the bus.
"However, it did not reach any conclusion on this point.
To tell the truth, she is not too interested in buses, but rather in the points system, the maximum speed on the motorway and the use of mobile phones while driving," says expert Hořín.
"The Ministry of Transport does not consider the activity of stewards as something that would fundamentally jeopardize the safety of passengers," Hanzelka said, adding that the control of bus safety is under the authority of the police and the Occupational Safety Authority.
Czech referees fight for seabed
It approaches an electronic wall chart, on which Australia and adjacent marine areas are depicted.
However, he is not interested in the continent, but in a small point lost in the blue of the ocean.
"The island belongs to Australia, as does the adjacent seabed.
Yet this area is as big as the continent itself," says Italian jurist Luigi Santosuosso, who is part of the thirty-member team of the UN Division for Ocean Affairs and the Law of the Sea.
Its head, the director of the division, Czech lawyer Václav Mikulka, follows the presentation and supplements it from time to time.
Hard work and enthusiasm characterize the prevailing atmosphere.
The seabed hides a world little known until now, rich in natural resources.
It can contain oil, minerals and other mineral resources, but also previously unknown living organisms, which may hold the key to the development of a cancer drug.
A bottom larger than land
Coastal states have now begun to vehemently aspire to new underwater territories.
According to a UN convention, they use their rights, which they agreed on in 1982 in Montego Bay, Jamaica.
This is mainly the area of the so-called continental shelf, which often extends several hundred kilometers from the coast of the given country.
The latter may, according to the convention, claim exclusively all the resources of the continental shelf.
"To put it simply, continental shelf is considered to be the part of the seabed and its subsoil, which is a natural extension of the continent under the sea.
It extends beyond the limits of the coastal sea, often also beyond the two hundred nautical miles that represent the so-called exclusive economic yone," Mikulka explains.
The request that the country in question submits to the Commission for the establishment of the external borders of the continental shelf must be supported by extensive scientific-technical documentation, based on numerous costly surveys and metrises.
It is the result of several years of preparatory work.
"One of our roles is to provide the commission with legal and scientific-technical assistance.
So far, the committee has dealt with five applications, from Russia, Brazil, Australia, Ireland and New Zealand.
So far, only the last three countries mentioned have been successful," Mikulka adds.
Australia's success, which was the first to significantly expand its underwater possessions, has recently gained global recognition.
New Zealand, too, has gained territory - the extent of the seabed, allocated to it by the commission last week, is 1.6 million square kilometres, which is the size of the country multiplied by six.
Both countries have invested millions of dollars in prospecting.
The benefit they will derive in the future from the exploitation of the seabed will, as they project, be invaluable.
Gradually, other countries will also submit their request.
They may do so within ten years of ratifying the "Montego Bay Convention".
There, where the continental shelf ends, begins the area of the ocean floor, proclaimed by convention "common heritage of humanity".
There, no state enjoys an exclusive position.
The right of extraction in this zone is granted by an international institution established by convention.
"Nevertheless, make no mistake, the seabed is not a Klondike," says director Mikulka, exaggerating, adding that "its areas are precisely clearly defined and their regime anchored in a contract".
Czechs in the Pacific
Part of the seabed today also belongs to the Czech Republic.
It shares it with other states of the former Eastern bloc within the framework of the common organization "Interoceanmetal".
In 1991, the latter, together with investors from a few other States, obtained the status of a so-called "pioneer investor" under the Convention.
It has the right to mine in the ClarionClipperton Zone in the Pacific Ocean, located between Mexico, the Hawaiian Islands and Kiribati.
The area prospected by the investor slightly exceeds the area of the former Czechoslovakia.
The background is hectic, it is a kind of underwater replica of the Tatra.
"It is possible to extract on an area with a total area of 75,000 square kilometers.
The area represents a rich deposit of polymetallic concretions containing nickel, copper, cobalt and manganese," said Ind Pakshi Rajan, another lawyer.
Rober Sandev, a Macedonian employee of the division, provides an example of such a concretion.
