The hopes of the people of Düsseldorf rest on Frankfurt.
There was no shortage of big words in the letter sent by the WestLB Board of Directors to the employees of the house.
Through a union of the entities of the financial institute of Düsseldorf with the Deka-Bank of Frankfurt, "the central institution of the financial markets of the financial group of the Sparkasse" could be constituted, according to the letter made public Monday.
WestLB would bring a "competence block" coupled with sustainable productivity in such a case.
All in all, such a relationship could be the decisive kick-off to further mergers in the banking sector of the Länder.
This is what it looks like when a steering committee wants to demonstrate its ability to act in difficult times.
Because the injured WestLB is still under great pressure.
It is not only the European Commission, but also the Federal Financial Services Supervisory Authority that has only recently made it clear to the government of the Land of North Westfalia that time is running out in the search for a future solution.
However, there has been talk for some time now - also on the Frankfurt side - of a relationship of some form between Deka Bank, which knows Sparkasse's customers through their investment funds, and WestLB.
Deta-Bank chief Franz Waas made it clear during the presentation of the half-year figures at the end of August that he did not see any point in merging the house on Mainzer Landstrasse with a state bank, be it Helaba or WestLB.
However, the board of directors of Deka, each half of which is supported by both the banks of the Länder and the savings bank groups, instructed the steering committee to conduct talks with WestLB with a view to joint commercial activities.
This could be the flow from the financial market, or parts of it.
However, talks have only just begun, according to the financial centre.
This is not the first time that Deta-Bank, which with its 3,000 employees is one of the largest employers in Frankfurt's financial centre, has come into play when it comes to consolidating the savings bank sector.
In 2003 it was thought for a while that Deta-Bank could merge with the Rhineland-Palatinate and Halbab.
Yet nothing came out of this ternary bouquet.
No sooner had the plans been made public than the Hessian government decided against any participation by Hellaba in them.
Subsequently, the other two houses did not meet either.
The Bank of the Land of Rhineland-Palatinate was instead attached to the Bank of the Land of Baden-Wüttenberg in Stuttgart.
But there have always been new negotiations on the merger of Deka-Bank with banks in the Länder.
Finally, however, Günther Merl, chairman of the board of directors of Hellaba, spoke out against any commercial strategy of merging with his bank.
Quite apart from this, there seems to be a growing feeling that the consolidation of the various public sector institutions is particularly urgent.
Now that the election to the Bavarian state parliament has passed, a union of BayernLB with the Baden-Wuttenberg state bank could materialise first.
For Helaba, this is not particularly good news.
If the pressure to merge should increase, potential partners are gradually slipping away.
In the South, it would now be a junior partner, although it has so far weathered the crisis better than the banks in Munich and Stuttgart.
The Hessen-Thuringian Savings and Transfer Group, which owns 85 percent of Helaba's capital, closed any union with WestLB at the beginning of the year.
NordLB would remain at a pinch.
Such geo-strategic reflections, however, reflect only one facet.
Another facet is how the different business models of each of these banks can match.
In June, Merl stated that the decisive question of the future capacity of the banks in the Länder should be ensured had not yet been resolved by the German Savings and Credit Transfers Group.
Eventually, a carving up of the WestLb could take place, a carving up which here is obviously not desired.
This is also what the letter of the current management committee is about: in any case, a 'global solution' for the institution would be targeted.
How all this will be lumped together with the union of certain entities with Deta-Bank remains to be seen.
