Sleepless nights for Hypo Real Estate shareholders
The German banking system is relatively stable, insisted the Federal Finance Minister only a few weeks ago.
How fortunate that the politician used the word 'relatively' and slipped that the German banking sector would not be spared from crisis movements.
It did indeed happen this weekend.
The Bavarian real estate financier Hypo Real Estate (HRE), listed on the DAX, obtains from a consortium of German banks a loan of one billion to protect itself from market turbulence.
A person in the confidence of the situation told Reuters on Monday that aid credits are issued up to an amount of 35 billion euros.
Hypo Real Estate would now have to pay interest on the fraction to which it would be entitled.
The money comes as much from private banks as from banks under public law.
In the background, it is the daughter company Depfa that bears the losses.
The state financier had, according to a newspaper article, refinanced himself in the very short term for long-term projects for which he had borrowed money - which is no longer possible because of mistrust of the markets.
In the first half of 2008, the bank's liquidity reserve was reduced by 95% to €2.37 million, while the equity ratio also fell slightly from 1.6% to 1.45%.
Profits outstanding and net profits from financial transactions had fallen to zero compared to the same period the previous year, profits from the assignment of receivables and specified securities and the termination of provisions in credit operations had fallen by more than 70 per cent to €5 million.
And it was only thanks to the large profits from the reimbursement of downstream accounting costs from the restructuring of the former Depfa Group, as well as the reimbursement of interest according to the book of tax procedures and commercial purchases for Konzern companies, that the earnings deficit of about 16 percent turned out to be moderate.
After its privatization in 1990, the former state financier had first speculated badly on industrial real estate loans, which had then been subsidized at the Aareal bank.
Because traditional state financing was not profitable enough, Depfa then became more intensively involved in infrastructure projects and in the financing of projects jointly between private investors and the State (Privat-Public-Partnership, PPP) and diversified internationally.
On the value of the daughter company, Hypo Real Estate must carry out depreciation which should have an essential material effect on the calculation of the group's gains and losses which is nevertheless rather unclear.
The fact is that dividends have been cut.
Already for 2007, they had been truncated by two-thirds.
Since the acquisition of Depfa, Hypo Real Estate has been a highly important state and infrastructure investor.
It is stronger than other institutions dependent on refinancing on the inter-bank market since it has no customer deposits.
With the collapse of the investment bank Lehman Brothers two weeks ago, credit allocation between banks has again dried up considerably as banks have accumulated liquidity.
Hypo Real Estate needs annually for a part - about 50 billion euros - of all Depfa loans from a short-term means of refinancing.
According to a press release from Hypo Real Estate, the group's financing requirement is covered with medium-term credit and the company protected from the influence of international financial markets largely out of order at present.
Other sources say that refinancing would be ensured with the funds until the end of 2009.
On the other hand, Georg Funke, Chairman of the Executive Board of HRE explained that the Hypo Real Estate Group should no longer have to resort to the financial markets in the medium term.
