Rats also have sensations
A rat or a cockroach flees from danger, does that mean that he also feels fear?
Neurophysicist Joseph LeDoux is convinced: many animals also have sensations.
But how can we verify that he feels the same way when he behaves in the same way as we do?
In the online magazine "Edge", contributions have been published for several years by famous scientists.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents in a series of articles answers to the question "What do you think is true without being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have sensations and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else having been able to prove it until now, just as it cannot be proven that other human beings have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope that all human brains have the same configuration.
As soon as we turn to other species and address the questions of feeling or in general consciousness, we enter difficult to penetrate because the Hardware does not correspond.
When a rat is in danger, it does the same thing as many other animals: it plays dead, flees or attacks.
Human beings behave in the same way, which is why some scientists deduce a comparable subjective experience.
However, I do not believe it.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transpose our subjective experience to that of animals.
One aspect is that the circuits almost always associated with human consciousness include the lateral prefrontal cortex (because of its participation in short-term memory and in the functions of direction and execution).
This vast region is much more developed in humans than in other primates and appears to be entirely absent in other beings.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, including the awareness of who we are, and the ability to predict and decide, it is reasonable to assume that the human being differs even from other primates.
Another significant peculiarity could lie in the linguistic nature of man: since much of his existence is related to language, this often means that his consciousness depends on it.
In this case, animals could be excluded.
But even if consciousness were not to depend on language, language would surely influence it, so that animal consciousness, however it is produced, would probably differ greatly from most of our states of consciousness.
This is why it is so difficult to determine what consciousness can look like in other animals.
If this, internal and subjective, can neither be measured nor, because of this particular Hardware, analyzed based on our own experience, then its observation poses big problems for us.
Most of my developments refer to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness besides that should be more easily accessible scientifically.
One could examine the consciousness processes of animals without considering their content, and this is exactly what has happened in studies of the short-term memory of primates, particularly with the example of visualization.
But in this approach followed by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, we focus more on the nervous correlations of consciousness than on the causal mechanisms: the two can be identical or not.
Curiously, this approach also highlights the weight of the Prefrontal Cortex in the realization of visualization.
But what then results for emotions?
I conclude that an emotional system such as fear is activated in a brain conscious of its own activity.
What we call "fear" is therefore the mental state in which we find ourselves when the activity of the defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as the reactions of the body) monopolizes the living memory.
Thus observed, emotions are closely linked to the regions of the cortex that characterize primates and especially humans.
Subtle degrees of feeling, associated with our voluble nature, emerge, because we can, with the help of words and grammar, differentiate and categorize states to impute them to others than to ourselves.
In contrast, Antonio Damasio, for example, thinks that sensations from primitive activities arise in the bodily sensation regions of the cortex and brainstem, as does Jaak Pankseep, who focuses more on the brainstem.
As this network has not changed much during human evolution, it could quite participate in transverse sensations of all kinds.
From a purely theoretical point of view, I cannot contradict it, but I believe it is unprovable.
Pankseep argues that what appears as fear in humans and rats is probably also felt as such in both cases: how could we verify whether rats and humans feel the same way when they behave in a similar way?
A cockroach flees from danger, but what if he feels fear?
In my opinion, similar behaviours are not enough to prove identical experiences.
Certainly, the nervous comparison helps: rats and humans have similar brain trunks, cockroaches on the other hand do not even have a brain.
But is the brain stem the cause of sensations?
And even if we could prove this for humans: how could we demonstrate it in rats?
I believe that rats and other mammals, maybe even cockroaches (who knows?) have sensations.
But I wouldn't know how to prove it.
And because their sensations are likely completely different from ours (since human consciousness relies on special circuits and language), I'd rather explore the emotional behavior than the emotional sensations of rats.
In any case, progress is emerging on the nervous level insofar as we gauge the same thing in rats and in humans.
Since I don't explore language and consciousness in rats, or sensations, I don't know if they exist.
You might think of it as short-term, but I'd rather move forward than constantly bang against a wall.
I am indeed a pragmatic emotional.
