For years, a mysterious phenomenon has caused confusion among researchers - the anomaly of gravitational support.
Gravitational support is a maneuver of space probes, by which they obtain an additional impulse in the gravitational field of a celestial body, the Earth for example.
Thus, probes can save a lot of fuel.
The American-European research probe Cassini-Huygens used this physical trick, as did the Ulysses solar probe.
This is what has surprised researchers for years: flying objects do not always behave 100 percent as expected according to the venerable laws of gravitation.
Moreover, irregularities appear in terms of speed.
The probes become unexpectedly faster or slower.
Until now, physicists could not explain this effect.
They called it the gravitational support anomaly.
Some experts feared that Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity, which describes the attractive force of matter due to the curvature of space, might not be entirely correct.
American physicist Stephen Adler of the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton still firmly believes that Einstein was not wrong and is trying to explain the gravitational support anomaly using what is called dark matter that astronomers have identified in the universe.
"Dark matter could be responsible for this anomaly, which is also found near Earth," he writes.
Space researchers have only known about dark matter for about ten years.
It apparently emanates from it a force of attraction whose effect is observable on other celestial bodies.
