Five paragraphs in the Florida Guide transformed this city, located just off Route 17, a road that runs through the often forgotten central Florida that culminates in a chapter of black history and human drama.
Bold as a bass drum in life and literature, Hurston led readers to the owned store of Eatonville's first mayor, Mr. Joe Clarke, which was later divided into several private parts.
"Past the road on the left," she writes, "you will find the modern brown and white public school, with its gardens and well-preserved playgrounds that Howard Miller has always cared for, although he can barely read and write.
She also mentioned Widow Dash's new husband and wrote that Lee Glenn "sells drinks of all kinds as well as anything that can be used by people passing through.
So, in just a hundred words, Hurston associated Eatonville with self-government but also with illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
Of course, Fodor was not like that.
It wasn't actually a portrait that everyone enjoyed.
Zora described the reality well," said Ella Dinkins, 90, one of Johnson's young daughters whom Hurston immortalized, citing the colorless songs, performed by men who praised their beauty.
She added: "Some people didn't like it."
Hurston is still remembered as a lively and eccentric person, who returned frequently after his family moved to Jacksonville, Fla.
Augustus Franklin, 77, recalled that Hurston usually arrived in town without warning in a big Chevrolet with a cigarette in his mouth and pants here, where even today people are proud of traditional clothes.
Many residents were fascinated, Mr. Franklin said, while many mocked her.
"People were always happy to see Zora," he said.
But he further adds, swinging in his chair on the back patio overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was certainly baptized, that "she never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were out of production.
Eatonville and the whole world seemed to have forgotten her.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the '20s, she was buried in a grave of some kind, at Fort Pierce, Fla, where she lived.
In Eatonville, no major commemorations, nor plaque for the general public.
I don't think they understood the contribution or legacy she offered to the world," said Valerie Boyd, author of "Wrapped in Rainbows," a biography of Hurston published in 2003.
A crucial moment occurred in the 1980s.
Orange County public officials wanted to move a five-lane highway into the city to replace Kennedy Boulevard, the community's two-lane main street.
The development of Orlando has already pushed Interstate 4 to the west corner of the city.
The proposal was made as Eatonville was just recovering from a difficult period in its history.
Forced integration, among many other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of the community.
In the 50s, the dispute over the mixing of races led hatred to the doors of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of young white people would throw oranges or objects at the people sitting on the side," Franklin said.
" One lady even died. "
They threw a watermelon from their car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's request for forced integration, defining its decision in Brown v. Board of Education "insulting rather than glorifying of my race".
Residents now proclaim that the elimination of racial segregation in schools, while positive in some aspects, has diluted Eatonville's cohesion and weakened the confidence of young people.
"Black children used to be kissed - I remember this well - we kissed our master in the morning, and in the evening too," said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Ella Dinkins and chief director of the Eatonville Community Safeguard, a non-profit group.
This lasted, she added, until teachers and students no longer came from the same place.
"You don't kiss your white teacher because he's white — I mean there's a cultural dividing line here," Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, by the way, created space for many more Zora Neale Hurston—black writers, actors, and artists who went beyond the prejudice, like herself, armed with a joyful self-confidence and guidelines such as, "How can they deprive themselves of the pleasure of my company!"
It's beyond me."
In 1975, writer Alice Walker visited the unmarked grave in Hurston and began struggling to revive its reputation.
Five years later, an acclaimed biography of Hurston by Robert E. Hemenway, a true bestseller, reintroduced it to the American canon.
The highway project came just as Eatonville's most famous girl had regained her appeal.
And this time, Hurston's old neighbors see her as a savior.
The community began organizing a Hurston festival to demonstrate the catastrophic consequences of this highway.
Hundreds of fans came to the festival's inauguration two years later, and many return in January, to commemorate it.
After many years, the county rejected the highway proposal.
"The fiasco of the five-lane motorway, extremely fast, a real civic pride," said Melle. Nathiri.
Miss Boyd summed it all up stating that "Zora saved Eatonville".
The victory against the highway project allowed him to change his own image.
Non-residents, like Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who has been attending our church since 1993, began to come in large numbers, and residents began to reconsider the past.
Eatonville has been listed as a historic town since 1998.
A mono-themed library (obviously renamed Hurston) opened in 2006, on a beautiful Kennedy Boulevard, repaved.
Today, Eatonville remains an anomaly for Florida: six miles from Orlando, it can at any time consider itself a back street on a rainy summer day, small as it was when it was founded by 27 black families in the 1880s.
(90 percent black today)
Outsiders who come to discover the history of Eatonville, its raison d'être, are still treated with caution.
You have to ask permission for most interviews, and some things—like the walls of the old church in Eatonville, painted by the white man, depicting black men in the fields—don't have to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Ms. Jones, a courageous teacher with a soft spot for bright red, are still afraid that their island community will be well understood.
However, with the expansion of the Hurston Festival, a certain level of local pride has emerged.
Young people in particular tend to view Eatonville as Hurston viewed his entire race: beautiful, problematic and all, no better or worse, but as proud, creative, bossy, crazy and mixed as other ethnic and racial groups in America.
It is genuine civic affection that can be heard in the voice of Mr. Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, who plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or for the police force, which needs additional forces.
And even for the youngest, like Winter Park twins 11-year-old Alondra and Alexia Kenon, seem to have learned the Eatonville description correctly.
"Most people who pass through this area will think, 'Oh, this city has nothing compared to others,'" Alondra Kenon said after mass last Sunday.
But if you stop and take the time to contemplate history, it's a very beautiful city."
