Still, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from the kiosk and giant TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn't realize they're in the eye of the storm.
They could never think that in the glass-comb offices above their heads, the bankers and hedge fund managers who monopolize New York, spend the worst "office day" since the crack of 1929.
