Latinos still hang out between residential buildings wearing, like mules, fifty luxurious shirts hanging from a yoke placed on his shoulders.
Office workers continue to line up to buy their morning sandwiches from street vendors, and it's still impossible to find a taxi between 4 and 7 p.m. on weekdays.
I hadn't felt the crisis despite the completely pessimistic narratives until this afternoon when I decided to open a new savings account.
Fortunately, I had planned to work in the late afternoon, because I discovered at my local subsidiary of JP Morgan Chase, about twenty people queuing.
Not in front of the tellers' counters, nor to withdraw cash or make a payment, but in front of the customer service counter, where regular customers ordered their checkbooks, tourists asked for directions to the Macy store, and new customers opened accounts.
Most of those in front of me, I would later learn from Starr, my "authorized personal banker," were all lining up for the same reason I did.
Not in the same way, because they had already withdrawn their savings from smaller banks, such as those in New Jersey, Pennsylvania, and Staten Island.
They have withdrawn their money from savings accounts called thrifts (such as a construction company), credit associations, and the type of local savings banks and their subsidiaries that operate only in one state, and who say they treat customers like their family.
