The office and store employees in front of me, frightened of another potential debacle, have transferred their money to a bank that seems reliable to them, the one that does the most bailouts on Wall Street.
Nonsensital New Yorkers have become very familiar with the world of finance in recent weeks.
"I could hear a lady at my local Chinese supermarket talking on the phone about Lehman Brothers, the bank that failed, and its meagre chief executive Dick Fuld, with the same familiarity she might have had for criticizing a colleague.
