Memoirs of Vernon Handley, and William Woodruff.
Mark Brown writes: Music director at Guildford since 1962, Vermon "Tod" Handley (died 11 September) was responsible for the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and Choir.
Already part of his musical project for the city, he founded the following year, the fantastic youth choir, Proteus.
The choir was supposed to include those under 21, but before Proteus could sing his last song in 1979, many of us who were over 20 refused to give up the choir.
The name "Proteus" (which changed shape according to mythology) represented the willingness and ability of the choir to handle any type of music presented to it, whether madrigal or messianic.
The musical versatility produced by such a young choir was often impressive, always exciting, thanks to the inspiration of one man, and his enthusiasm for music, which remained constant over the years.
Remember how Tod told us to "let the music speak for itself".
He is said to have said: "The composer knows what he wants"
It's all there, in the music.
So sing!"
His wand technique was absolutely clear, precise, even if never dictatorial or appearing.
Whatever the musical standard, he raised it much higher.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If a driver were to be knighted, it was Vernon Handley.
I knew him well during the decades from 1962 to 1982, when he was conducting the Guildford Philharmonic.
Over the past 40 years, I've seen over a hundred of his concerts, and I can honestly say that none of them have ever disappointed me – and, sometimes, they've even inspired me.
Tod Handley held this combination of greatness and personal modesty so rarely.
He hated drivers who, according to him, "only focus on certain people".
He will be missed by many.
William Woodruff
Professor John Beckett writes:
Your obituary of William Woodruff (who died September 25) states that "in 1946 he resumed his studies in economic history at Oxford and in 1950 became a member of Houblon-Norma research, while doing a BSc, MA and PhD."
This is what comes from Woodruff's letter in Beyond Nab End, but it is not correct.
From 1946 to 1953 he was Professor of Economic History at the University of Nottingham, and at the same time completed a PhD thesis on the British plastics industry, under the supervision of Professor J.D. Chambers; it was then published in 1958 as The British Rubber Industry.
In the 50s and 51s in the United States, he studied at the Norman Hops, and in the summer of 1952, at the universities of Illinois, Harvard and New York.
In 1953 he left Nottingham for Illinois.
Why Woodruff chose to hide this part of his past remains unknown.
Muslim graves desecrated as Austria swings to the right.
Heinz-Christian Strache, who has abandoned the right wing of the Austrian Freedom Party and Filip Dewinter of the Belgian right Vlaams Belang, take part in a demonstration to present the organization of "cities against Islamization" in Antwerp, Thursday, January 17, 2008.
They carry road signs depicting mosques striped red.
Police accuse far-right extremists of desecrating an Austrian Muslim cemetery on the weekend of the victory of far-right political parties in the country's general election.
More than 90 graves were seriously damaged at the Traun cemetery, near Linz, between Friday night and this morning; According to the police, this is an organized action.
The offenders painted Jewish symbols such as the Star of David on several graves; Detectives believe, however, that this could have been done to disguise extremists' sense of hatred towards Muslim immigrants.
Could this accident somehow be related to the elections.
A spokesman for the local Islamic community said it was "deeply shocked" at news of the desecration, which comes just during the religious month of Ramadan, which is coming to an end.
Austria is seriously considering regaining its courage, following its rightward swing in yesterday's parliamentary elections.
The two far-right parties that won almost 30 percent of the vote, the Freedom Party and the Alliance for the Future of Austria, waged an anti-immigration campaign. Some of their slogans were even considered, according to critics, xenophobic.
Heinz-Christian Strache, the Freedom Party leader who won more than 18 percent of the vote, campaigned against headscarves and burkas, and even voiced opposition to alaha food.
During his final race in Vienna, he spoke of "a European brotherhood" to avoid the rise of Islam.
Both parties are trying to prevent the construction of mosques and minarets, claiming that they would be a political symbol of the Islamization of Austria and Europe.
Polls and analyses carried out just after the elections defined the far right as the strongest political bloc in the country, which is demonstrated by the majority of young voters who made the difference, because they were worried about their future in the European Union.
Gary Glitter is banned from travelling abroad.
Courts have banned glamorous rock star Gary Glitter, accused of child sexual abuse, expatriation in France and Spain.
The magistrates imposed a six-month ban on Glitter, after he told the authorities under his control of his intention to travel to Spain via the France.
Police in Kent issued the travel ban last Thursday after proving Glitter's guilty child sexual abuse to magistrates.
Glitter, or his real name, Paul Gadd, was not present at the hearing at the Ashford Courts of Limited Jurisdiction, but was still represented by his lawyer Corker Binning.
A court spokesman said: "On Thursday 25 September at Ashford Magistrates' Court, Kent Police requested an app to prevent Mr Paul Gadd from travelling to France and Spain until 25 March.
"Paul Gadd was not present then."
Glitter, 64, informed authorities that he wanted to go abroad, even if it meant being included in the list of accused of sexual abuse.
He must inform the authorities if he wishes to go abroad for more than three days.
He must also inform the police, 7 days before his scheduled departure date.
If he does not report his movements to the authorities, he could serve up to five years in prison.
Kent police said they would not discuss specific cases or Glitter's potential movements in the county.
A spokesman for Kent Police said: "Kent Police will do everything necessary to protect our children as well as those overseas.
"In our view, it is easier to monitor someone who stays in the UK because we have arrangements that can handle any potential risks, much more effectively.
"Protecting the people of Kent is Kent Police's most cherished intention, and we are closely monitoring the behaviour of those accused of sexual abuse in the area, to minimise potential risks to the public."
. Glitter returned to the UK last month after serving 27 months in a Vietnamese prison for abusing two girls, aged 10 and 11, respectively.
When he was released, Glitter flew to Bangkok from where he should have boarded a flight to London.
But he declared that he was not feeling well, and refused to leave for London.
The Thai authorities blocked him at passport control, and in the end, he left for Hong Kong.
The Chinese authorities refused him entry to their territory, and was therefore forced to return to Bangkok; Thai police and immigration officers insisted that he return to England.
He finally arrived at Heathrow Airport's Terminal 3 on 22 August and stayed there while his lawyer, David Corker, went to Uxbridge Limited Court, West London, to register him on Scotland Yard's list of accused of sexual abuse.
In the past, Glitter had already served a four-month sentence in the UK, for possessing child abuse images.
An Interior Ministry source said Jacqui Smith, the Home Secretary, was reassured and pleased to know that Glitter had been banned from travel to France and Spain.
"I photograph the master off stage to capture elements of his character" Günther Bauer - Photographer
No heels, no gift clothes.
The essence of the great masters of flamenco, freed from all tensions to achieve the relaxed aspect of man or woman.
On the one hand the artist.
On the other, the person.
Inseparable except in intimacy, in these moments unknown to the general public, where we discover intimate gestures and stolen looks artists who do not care to go on stage.
The German Günther Bauer mixes in "Flamenco - people" the theatricality of some staging with singers, dancers and guitarists with this lesser-known side of artists.
In this project, the photographer takes up the particular iconography of flamenco from different angles.
Included in the programming of the Flemish Month of Photography, the exhibition "reflects the international importance of flamenco, greater every day", explains the creator, who clarifies that "Flamenco - people" "can be anyone but, after seeing the photos, the observer realizes that they are not typical images of artists on stage.
These people photographed "in the street" are artists capable of transmitting passion, sadness, joy on stage ... captivating the audience.
To capture moments of personality of these artists it is not necessary to take pictures on stage.
They have a personality and a character of their own.
What interested me was to create an intimate atmosphere that allowed me to capture with the camera moments of personality of flamenco stars".
With the festival "Chant populaire des Mines", Bauer began in 1997 a long journey to photograph singers, guitarists or dancers with a plate camera.
These are portraits that, thanks to the choice of camera and equipment, recall classic photography.
The implementation of different stylistic means breaks with the classical side of the image, giving it a touch of modernity, this reflects the perception of flamenco according to Bauer: "A music with very traditional roots that evolves and surprises every day".
It is not about the dance or the song per se, but about the personality and character of the artist who captivates the audience with his art.
The search for the essential and the magic has been the constant of this work that is presented these days at the El Fotómata gallery.
Flamenco stars like Diego El Cigala, Chano Lobato, Cristina Hoyos, Enrique Morente, El Lebrijano, Antonio Canales, Vicente Amigo, among others, are part of the selection made from about seventy artists photographed.
The project has turned into a flamenco anthology, which will soon be published in a book of collections of portraits exhibited at the gallery.
Bauer's passion for portraits led him to repeat the idea two years ago with the "Portraits of Old Sportsmen" ("SportARTproject").
Although the concepts are different in "Flamenco - people", the photographer admits that he loves to photograph the portrait of people, to know them and to be able to enter their lives for a more or less long time.
I believe that in photography the portrait is the most difficult genre.
You find yourself in front of people, characters that sometimes you do not know or who leave you only a few minutes to be able to take a picture of them.
Despite these circumstances, as a photographer, I always try to make my ideas come true."
This collection of portraits of the current flamenco entitled "Flamenco - people", is exhibited at the El Fotómata Gallery, located at number 20 Calle de la Mata (street parallel to the Poplar Garden of Hercules) which will be open until October 16th.
Vargas Llosa confesses that the novel he is writing is "real audacity"
The novel is set in places that no one knows and deals with unknown subjects, but once again, Mario Vargas Llosa is determined to advance the new project he is working on, a novel that stars Roger Casemant, an Irish nationalist who lived twenty years in Congo and passed through the Amazon.
The favorite for the Nobel Prize in Literature confessed yesterday at the Hay festival Segovia, that the novel that currently occupies him "is a real audacity" and that "everything shows that he should not write it".
"If I were reasonable, I wouldn't do it, but I will do it and I hope to finish it," he concluded in his speech at the four-day festival for the exchange of ideas and thoughts, which for four days saw a hundred writers, historians and journalists and thousands of people parade through the city of the aqueduct.
The author of "The City and the Dogs" was the most anticipated character of the third edition of this festival and fulfilled his contract.
Vargas Llosa, who won the Hay Festival prize with a majority of the participants' votes, was sold out at the Juan Bravo Theatre.
The presenter of the Festival, Félix Romeo, found himself in front of a fascinated audience that did not see the past hour during which the Peruvian, with a prodigious memory and with a great dose of humor, traced the birth of his literary vocation, which is due to "his thirst to read" and "to live new experiences"; how he wrote in a "very methodical way" through intense documentation work, correcting and rewriting part of the text to cope with his "lack of inspiration"; how Faulkner, Victor Hugo and Alexandre Dumas influenced his vocation and how his memories inspire his novels.
The Spanish-American novelist acknowledged that "there is no way" to measure and know if books are life-changing. "But I refuse to believe that literature is pure amusement, an ephemeral experience," said Vargas Llosa, who said that it "has effects" and "makes people less alike," because writers have been asked "not to indulge in frivolity" and to assume their vocation.
