Police control of a van in the province of Alava: two thousand kilos of hashish found
Five o'clock minus ten in the morning.
Traffic control of the police of Euskadi (l'Ertzaintza) at the border of the Municipality of Armiñón (Alava).
Police officers arrested two occupants of a van and the two fled.
Its loading, more than two tons of hashish, enough to stop them.
The police pursued them and arrested one of the two occupants, a 28-year-old man, identified as A.A.J., according to information disclosed by the Department of the Interior of the Basque Government.
The arrested individual was charged with drug trafficking and falsification of documents.
The incident took place when various officials of the Traffic Unit of Alava were carrying out a check of vehicles on the N-1, at the border of the Municipality of Armiñón.
They were about to stop a van to inspect it when the driver disobeyed orders, suddenly accelerated and the control began.
The police began their pursuit until the vehicle stopped two kilometers further on the side of the road, where the two occupants descended to flee into a wooded area.
Basque police eventually arrested one of the two occupants and seized the 2,178 kilograms of hashish they were transporting and found after inspecting the van, an Iveco Daily.
The rear part of the vehicle was loaded with bales of hashish. Then they transferred him to a police station for a thorough inspection and to weigh the drugs.
In addition, the officials found that the license plate had been "forged" since it did not coincide with the one written on the van's registration document, which is also why they charged the detainee with the crime of falsifying documents.
The Ertzaintza continues its investigation to arrest the other suspect, who managed to escape, and to determine the source of the seized drugs.
The detainee, 28-year-old A.A.J., was taken into custody to carry out the various procedures and will be tried in the hours that follow.
Actress Heather Locklear arrested for driving under the influence of medication
Actress Heather Locklear, the famous Amanda from the TV series Melrose Place, was arrested this weekend in Santa Bárbara (California) for driving under the influence of a drug.
A witness saw her make strange maneuvers while trying to get out of her garage in Montecito, a spokesperson for the California Police Patrol revealed to People magazine.
The witness said that around 4:30 p.m., Locklear "pressed the accelerator hard, making a lot of noise, trying to get the car out of the garage, and going in reverse several times, she rolled on her sunglasses."
Shortly after, the witness, who at first did not recognize the actress, saw that Locklear stopped in the middle of the highway and got out of her vehicle.
This person, at that time, called emergency services because "he was worried about Locklear's life."
When the police patrol arrived they found the actress sitting inside her vehicle, which was partially blocking the road.
"She looked disoriented," which is why officers took her to the drug and alcohol center for testing.
According to a police spokesman, the actress was cooperative and alcohol abuse was ruled out from the start, although "based on police officers' observation at first glance, we thought Locklear was under the influence of medication."
Locklear was arrested on suspicion of driving under the influence of an unspecified substance and was incarcerated around 7.00pm and released a few hours later.
Two months ago, Locklear was discharged from the Arizona clinic where she was interned to treat a nervous breakdown.
Llamazares urged the Andalusian Federation of the United Left to assume its responsibilities in the Silva case
The General Coordinator and Deputy of the United Left, Gaspar Llamazares, said today that it is up to the regional federation to make a decision on the case of the former Councilor of Youth and Sports of the Municipality of Seville, Francisco Manuel Silva, who resigned last week after being accused of carrying out preferential treatment to members of his family.
"In these cases, I am very federalist, and it will be the Andalusian organization that will have to assume its responsibilities," Llamazares said of the behavior of the political party he will have to adopt in the Seville City Council.
However the leader of the United Left asked that the investigations show "transparency" for the irregularities that Silva may have committed: "The United Left has always defended this kind of case so that they have a maximum degree of transparency."
He also stressed that the political party has "very strict ethical codes for all civil servants".
"Sangre de Mayo", Garci's daring bet
Inspired by the stories of Benito Pérez Galdós, José Luis Garci recreates the famous battle of the Spanish against the French in "Sangre de mayo", which is the most ambitious film of his filmography with nearly 15 million euros budget.
The filmmaker tried "to stage the many characters and illustrate the social analysis" he has always admired in the work of the famous novelist, he explained today during the presentation of the film, with Quim Gutiérrez and Paula Echevarría at the head of the long list of actors.
The film with a duration of more than two and a half hours "Sangre de mayo" will be released in cinemas next Friday, which will then become a TV series for Telemadrid of more than four hours.
A great admirer of Galdós' literature, José Luis Garci claims to have realized with this shoot "a childhood dream" thanks to Esperanza Aguirre, who commissioned him, three years ago, to shoot a commemorative film for the two hundred years of May 2 in Madrid, something he always accepted when the story was confined to national historical facts.
The 15 million euros provided by the Municipality of Madrid constitute for Garci a "unique opportunity" to reproduce with the appropriate decorations and clothing the atmosphere of "a Spain that was the wrong leader for the fight, since, the struggle for independence led the people to rebellions under the reign of Ferdinand VII," he said.
But the filmmaker regrets not having obtained financing as for the films "Captain Alastrar" or "The Ghosts of Goya" - more than double that obtained for "Sangre de mayo" - because he could not shoot some scenes written in a script signed by Horacio Valcárcel, with whom he collaborated for most of his career.
The filmmaker of "Volver a empezar" has influenced his usual way of working, the staging of the actors, with whom he usually rehearses before starting filming and to whom he does not cast, since it seems to him "humiliating" and considers that "the role of the filmmaker is to go to the theater and the cinema to keep informed".
Many actors in "Sangre de mayo" rehearse in front of the camera, such as Miguel Rellán, Carlos Larrañaga or Fernando Guillén Cuervo.
A four-time Oscar nominee (he won one), Garci considers that the three candidate films that represent Spain this year at the Hollywood Academy "Sangre de mayo", "Seven French pool tables" and finally the winner, "Blind Sunflowers", are not representative of young Spanish cinema, "which deserves to be better known", he said.
With this film Garci does not expect a price.
"At first you think you're working for posterity, then you realize you're only working for prosperity, and now you're just making one more film," Garci says after more than 30 years of professional career.
Isabelle Bayón puts herself in the shoes of the Sevillian dancer Tórtola Valencia
A Sevillian dancer will pay tribute to a dancer who is also Sevillian.
Carmen Tórtola Valencia, daughter of a Catalan father (Florenç Tórtola Ferrer) and an Andalusian mother (Georgina Valencia Valenzuela), was born in the Triana district and at the age of three went to live in London with her family.
She was a free dancer and specialist in oriental dances.
She had an exciting life, a pioneer of women's liberation, like Isadora Duncan, Virginia Woolf or Sarah Bernhardt.
She was a Buddhist and vegetarian and advocated for the abolition of the corset that prevented the free movement of women.
The life of this woman, who marked the history of dance in Europe between the two world wars, fascinated Isabelle Bayón.
"I wanted to work with Pepa Gamboa and she asked me to play the Sevillian dancer Tórtola Valencia and it seemed incredible to me."
According to the dancer, "we are not trying to tell his life but to translate his way of thinking.
The titles of his dances made me think of flamenco.
Thus, "the butterfly dance" made me think of a Cuban folk dance and "the snake dance" of some tangos.
Her dancing was sensual and they told me that my way of dancing was identical to hers," she says.
The staging was made thanks to two remarkable contributions: that of Miguel Poveda who will sing Isabela again in one of his shows, as he did in "La puerta abierta"; and that of Professor Matilde Coral, who was exceptionally willing to collaborate with his student.
"Matilde transforms Tórtola into a mature character.
I am happy because she has agreed to play a role in my work and that honors me."
