The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of technologies for accident prevention, Nissan has been inspired, this time, by nature, especially bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, by imitating the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
It's called Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C and represents the first steps towards collision avoidance technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technical Center made the small robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, General Manager of Public Relations for Technology and Research and Development of Brand Management, the BR23C represents the rise of Nissan's safety shield.
This robot will allow the brand's vehicles to prevent collisions.
During its flight, each bee creates its own personal space in an oval shape that closely resembles the Nissan safety shield.
But the most important thing are the composed eyes of the bee, able to see at an angle of more than 300 degrees and in all directions, which allows it to fly without interruption inside its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers developed what is known as a laser range finder.
It detects obstacles that are within a distance of two meters and within a radius of 180 degrees, calculates the distance to this object and sends a signal to the microprocessor, immediately, to avoid the obstacle.
"The moment it detects an obstacle, the little robot will mimic the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by branching off its wheels 90 degrees or more to avoid collision.
The biggest difference from any other existing system is that the escape maneuver is totally instinctive.
If this were the case, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles," says Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Displacement Laboratory and lead engineer of this project.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot be diverted upwards or downwards, or diagonally; It can only move in two dimensions and according to what its wheels allow it and not in infinite directions like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, but also acceleration and deceleration, so that the small robot can avoid obstacles.
"Every second this device must only process information and act on this data.
It does not need to retain the information or intuitive logic of prior maneuvers, which is why it can run continuously with only a few dozen KB of memory.
It may come as a surprise, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even megabytes."
This represents the first bus to develop new instant collision avoidance technologies, a technology that will be introduced in production cars in a decade according to Nissan.
The robot works with lithium-polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
The other possible application of this technology in the future could be the adaptation of this device on a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles on the road.
