The Minister of the Interior wants the driver who has had more than three administrative penalties for alcohol, to have to install in his vehicle a system that prevents the vehicle from starting drunk, or if it does not blow.
The initiative was already announced last June and it now appears in the report of the Minister of State in which this initiative is considered a pilot project that will last one year.
Its goal is the rehabilitation of the driver by offering him road rehabilitation courses.
The Minister of State for Road Safety but also the Directorate General for Road Safety and the Technological Institute Foundation for Automotive Safety will participate in this initiative.
According to statistics, between 30% and 75% of motorists stopped for driving more than once drunk take back the car.
The alcolock would avoid this since it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the breath and prevents starting the vehicle if the driver does not blow before; or when the driver's alcohol level is higher than allowed.
Its cost is more than 1,000 euros and is the responsibility of the driver.
In this regard, a study conducted in the United States in 2007 showed that vehicles equipped with this device reduced violations by up to 65% in the first year of installation.
And in Spain it is estimated that it could save the lives of 115 people every year.
This measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to deal with such behaviour before it becomes a criminal offence.
And facilitate its implementation, since legal reform can be carried out by ordinary means, but, nevertheless, reform made by penal means requires a reform of the organic law.
The device is not yet available on the Spanish market in any commercial form, although some commercial and company vehicles already have one on an experimental basis.
Precisely tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on an initiative by the Spanish Socialist Party which proposes to install this system in school buses, as was done in France.
