Talking while sleeping
Some children talk during the night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very awake telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk in their sleep.
The first time it happens it may surprise you, but in reality it doesn't matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquia.
This is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
Of course, there is more than one who speaks during the night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life for example associated with an episode of high fever), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month ...), the day after the child does not remember anything.
There is no single cause that determines its occurrence
They are often linked to other sleep alterations such as nightmares, night terrors, bedwetting or sleepwalking, but this is not always the case.
As we have already said before, they can also be associated with very high fevers, stressful situations or overexcitement.
In any case, it is a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it occurs is also highly variable.
It may be that he speaks with a small quiet voice, with isolated words, whispers or on the contrary with cries, tears, long speeches ...
In the event that somniloquy becomes very common, it would be wise to observe the child and consult a specialist, to check if there is a problem that causes a lot of anxiety and to get an explanation for this problem.
We have said that it is a benign alteration, which is why there is no treatment unless it is related to another sleep alteration that can be cured (for example, if it is related to sleep apnea or stress).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child before going to sleep.
Therefore look for quiet games and avoid programs or television series that are more or less violent.
With children who are very nervous and have trouble relaxing, relaxation techniques can be used to help them calm down internally.
This will allow the child to have a more peaceful sleep.
As soon as somniloquies appear try to stay calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will not remember what happened.
Useful tips
Don't wake him up.
It is useless since he is unconscious and you would wake him up.
Even if he talks, he sleeps and rests.
