The interview - Blood back to safety
Yesterday, Héma-Québec celebrated the 10th anniversary of its founding, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, it regained the public trust that had been seriously shaken by the tainted blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is well known, the national blood supply managed by the Canadian Red Cross Transfusion Service was contaminated with acquired immunodeficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In response to this tragedy and public discontent, the Government of Canada instituted a public inquiry, chaired by Justice Horace Krever, in February 1994 to shed light on the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations to ensure that such a disaster does not happen again.
While Justice Krever was slow to table his report, some provinces then set up a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau committee fulfilled this mandate.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were created in Canada: Héma-Québec to serve Quebec and Canadian Blood Services to supply all the other provinces and the two territories.
"In 1998, when Héma-Québec began its activities, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Québec," recalls Dr. Décary.
The situation was discouraging.
Through efforts to improve the safety of blood products and fieldwork in the years that followed, we regained the public's trust," she says, before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, nearly 94% of Quebecers now had confidence in Héma-Québec.
However, Dr. Décary keeps in mind that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its creation on September 28, 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, there was an outbreak in Europe of many cases of the human form of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, says the one that has held the fort since its foundation in 1998.
"And we had no idea if this disease could be transmitted through blood.
We then relied on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know it and a serious disease can result, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain inevitably leading to death, we introduce exclusion measures.
In April 1999, blood was therefore refused to persons who had been in the United Kingdom for more than one month since 1980.
However, a few years ago, it was demonstrated beyond any doubt that this disease is transmitted through blood.
This episode showed us that the precautionary principle that we applied made sense."
In 1999, a much more sensitive technique for HIV testing appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests (NAT), which detect directly in the blood of donors the presence of the virus itself and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used until then were based.
TANs have shortened the silent period, which extends between the time the person was infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, explains the specialist.
This period was reduced to less than one week.
This has substantially reduced the risk that some donors will be infected without knowing it and cannot be detected.
These improvements have significantly reduced the risk of contracting AIDS through blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"In other words, it means that it will take 12 million blood products before someone becomes infected with HIV.
Since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will take more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission through a blood product occurs.
I believe that we can now feel comfortable receiving or prescribing a blood transfusion to regain health," said Héma-Québec's CEO.
"Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
You never know what pathogen will emerge in the system.
Just last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on Reunion Island, which, like West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
We must be constantly vigilant," continued Dr. Décary, before emphasizing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
"The needs are increasing because the population is aging.
Because cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need a recharge of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences on the blood donor network, which on average includes only 3% of Quebecers eligible to donate blood."
Any healthy person aged 18 and over who meets the eligibility criteria can donate blood every 56 days, or six times a year.
On average, 14 per cent of people who donate blood are not accepted, for example because they have AIDS or malaria, and if they have travelled to a malaria-affected country, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
"With this 3%, we are able to maintain an inventory that meets the needs of hospitals.
Shortages are very rare.
But we need to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer donate blood.
It is difficult to convince people to donate blood, but especially to retain them and encourage them to become regular donors.
Today's life is so hectic, we rarely find the time to spend an hour donating blood, "laments Francine Décary.
With an annual budget of $297 million, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for burn victims.
These tissues are analyzed, processed and frozen before being stored at Héma-Québec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Québec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered biomedical waste is full of blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
"We celebrated, a few weeks ago, the banking of our thousandth cord blood sample and we plan to collect more than a thousand per year.
We should start offering them for transplants early next year," says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Many mothers are disappointed not to be able to access it" because Héma-Québec does not have the means to offer this complex and expensive program in all Quebec hospitals.
