Quebec has built a lot in its relationship with the North, he stressed: the gold rush in Abitibi, Quebec engineering, James Bay.
"It's ours, it's our future," he added, after pausing theatrically to contemplate the huge map behind him.
The North, 70% of Quebec's territory, includes a portion of Labrador that Quebec has always claimed, said the premier at the press briefing.
"This is a traditional position that all governments have reiterated.
There is a border line on which there has been no agreement for a very long time and, when the opportunity arises, I reiterate this position on behalf of the government," he said.
Moreover, "with climate change, we need to rethink our vision of the North," he said of the Northwest Passage, which will open year-round due to melting ice.
In this new geopolitical context, the Prime Minister believes that occupying the territory is a duty.
What about the people of the territory, First Nations and Inuit?
The Prime Minister said that the Government of Quebec would be very attentive to them and that the project would benefit them, especially young people.
Two former ministers from two different parties, Pierre Corbeil and Michel Létourneau (former PQ MP for Ungava), have already begun consultations with some thirty communities.
An interdepartmental committee chaired by Benoît Pelletier and in which Julie Boulet (Transport and Natural Resources) has an important place has begun work.
The Prime Minister does not rule out a major meeting, "not necessarily a summit", but a moment when "we will give ourselves a common vision".
The development of the North would be consistent with the principles of sustainable development.
The Plan Nord will be "concerted, orderly and respectful of the environment," he promised.
Jean Charest described this "vision" as being in continuity with that of Liberal premiers who preceded him.
"Like the Liberals who came before us, we thought differently to turn challenges into new opportunities for growth and development."
This was one of the recurring themes of the weekend, which began Friday with a large cocktail to mark the 50th anniversary of Jean Lesage's arrival at the head of the party.
One of the resolutions adopted proposes to rename the Beauharnois Generating Station as the Adélard-Godbout Dam.
"From Godbout, who created Hydro-Québec, to Lesage, who made the Quiet Revolution and the nationalization of hydroelectricity, to Bourassa, who made James Bay, our party has forged the future," said Jean Charest.
In a press conference, he invoked another reference, conservative this one, the "Roads to the North" program of John Diefenbaker, Prime Minister from 1957 to 1963.
Addressing the Eastmain1a-Ruper hydroelectric dam project, Mr. Charest noted that its commissioning was scheduled for 2012.
"It's between us there, but I plan to be there," he told his activists, eliciting loud applause from them.
Indeed, the Prime Minister, who said in April that there would be no election in 2008 and probably not in 2009, did not rule out the possibility of calling an election this fall, which the law allows him to do.
He points out that his schedule is however fulfilled, including a mission of the Council of the Federation to China and a Quebec-New York summit.
The weekend's General Council provided the Liberal leader with a platform containing nationalist resolutions, including "constitutional aspirations" that passed like a letter in the mail: the QLP is calling in particular for the recognition of the "specificity of Quebec" in the Constitution.
He also wants Quebec to appoint members of the Canadian Radio-television and Telecommunications Commission and that they have a veto over decisions made in Quebec.
On the opposition side, the broad outlines of the Plan Nord were met with skepticism.
PQ leader Pauline Marois highlighted the Northern Quebec Development Policy that the Landry government launched in 2001.
According to her, the Liberal government, when it came to power in 2003, gave up on applying it.
If he had done so, "we would be more advanced today," commented Ms. Marois alongside her candidate in Jean-Talon (election that takes place today), Françoise Mercure.
The ADQ said it supports the adoption of a Plan Nord by the government.
"But what we want is that it's not just a show," said leader Sébastien Proulx, replacing Mario Dumont, who returns from vacation today.
Letters - A disgraced country
It was Mr. Vic Toews, former Minister of "Justice" (oh irony) in the Harper cabinet, who last summer allowed himself to say of Louise Arbour that she was a "disgrace" for Canada.
To cast aspersions on this woman who fought tirelessly for justice and who deserves all our admiration says as much about the Prime Minister's entourage as it does about Stephen Harper himself.
Here we are before a government that is the only one, among all the Western countries involved, not to have repatriated its national locked up in the Guantánamo concentration camp.
A government that takes no account of the fact that Omar Khadr was a very young teenager at the time of the alleged offences.
The only government that, despite the fact that Canada has signed the Geneva Convention, reneges on its word and allows a child soldier to languish in inhumane conditions.
The only one who relies on a travesty of justice to assess the guilt of the accused.
For the record, UNICEF, Amnesty International and the Canadian Bar Association, among others, are advocating for Omar Khadr's repatriation so that he can receive a fair trial in Canada.
This is the same government that turns a blind eye to torture: it does not care that a young adult is now psychologically destroyed, probably forever after so many years of abuse.
We don't realize it yet, but we are currently witnessing an insidious erosion of our rights, our freedom and our "democracy", the word that Harper keeps brandishing and ringing so hollow in his mouth.
The time has come when no morality no longer exists: we can abuse, torture, arbitrarily imprison a Canadian citizen at the whim of a hitherto minority head of government (what will happen after October 14...).
Many voters believe that they will find salvation in a party that advocates Virtue, Law and Order: they do not see that this government has renounced what made the reputation and dignity of our country.
The shame, Mr. Toews, is there, in this renunciation, and not elsewhere.
Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian speech
In its September 17 edition, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, Executive Vice-President of the Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
Pursuing an Orwellian logic, he claims that the world's largest gold company has filed a six-million-dollar defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small penniless publishing house in an effort to launch a "transparent public debate."
While it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth that they judge, especially in the case of defamation suits, but the law.
Not surprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely obscured by Mr. Garver.
For Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to ruin anyone who dares to support a position contrary to its own?
Regardless of the outcome of the trial, the authors and publisher of the book Noir Canada will have to spend considerable sums of money preparing their defence and fighting, on very unequal terms, against an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of the mining company.
The tactic in these unequal struggles is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose an out-of-court settlement that will gag the opposition and frighten anyone who dares to look into the matter again.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its vision of the facts to public opinion.
Unlike many of the countries where Barrick Gold operates, debates in Canada are normally conducted through the exchange of ideas and not with batons.
It was therefore enough for the mining company to open its books, its files and establish a real debate, through newspapers, media, publications and the funding of independent research teams that could have shed light on the issue.
But Barrick Gold seems not to trust public opinion and rejects out of hand petitions and letters of support for the authors of Black Canada.
Perhaps Mr Garver could explain how he can both call for a 'public' debate while at the same time disregarding the opinions of that same public?
In the vice-president's world, it seems that this word refers only to highly-paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; That is a rather narrow view of the concept.
In a democracy, even critics have a voice.
What Barrick Gold does not understand - or does not want to understand - is that the public that supports the authors and publishers of Black Canada does so primarily because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is ready to hear Barrick and judge, but on the basis of civilized exchanges of arguments, and not in the context of what many perceive as a SLAPP lawsuit (continuing the "public debate", Barrick Gold has just filed a formal notice against the authors of Noir Canada urging them to stop using this term...).
Beyond Mr. Garver's surreal speech, Barrick Gold's prosecution is a direct attack on academic freedom of research and the search for truth, which are essential to any democratic society.
It denies, en bloc, the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the very basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the wealthy corporations of this world in a country like Canada, or face repeated prosecution, who will be able to do that?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could do so following the scientific standards used by the authors of Black Canada.
It has a right of reply.
The academic community, to which we belong, has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold's outsized lawsuit makes it clear that, contrary to what it claims, it has no desire for transparent debate.
This is a loss for academia, as well as for public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place mechanisms to limit this kind of abusive prosecution.
Wall Street rescue operation - Democrats and Republicans agree
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republican and Democratic, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the biggest economic bailout since the Great Depression of the '30s.
The new version of the US$700 billion plan to curb the financial crisis that has rocked Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both houses of Congress.
It provides in particular: better control by elected officials of its implementation, new mechanisms to ensure the reimbursement of public money committed, new provisions to contain the number of houses seized for non-payment, as well as a right of scrutiny over the salaries paid to the managers of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and Republican Representative at the negotiating table Senator Judd Gregg announced the good news minutes after midnight yesterday at the end of a two-day marathon of negotiations.
"We have made great strides towards a deal that will be effective in the markets," said Bush Administration Representative Henry Paulson.
"Everything has been done in such a way as to shield the real economy and ordinary Americans from the ongoing crisis on Wall Street," she said.
"That's the fundamental point: If we don't do this, the trauma, chaos and disruption to the daily lives of Americans will be immense," said Republican Judd Gregg.
Negotiations had turned to a sprint in the last hours for fear of the effect that a new failure would have on the mood of investors.
The deadline we agreed was the opening of the markets this morning.
Late in the negotiations, the two candidates for the US presidential election were rather favorable to the agreement, without failing to express their dissatisfaction that we are forced to reach this extreme.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama took credit for adding certain provisions to the agreement, including the one to allow homeowners to keep their homes and the one on the salaries of executives of companies rescued by the state.
"When taxpayers are asked to take extraordinary measures because of the irresponsibility of some, there is nothing to be happy about.
But these measures are necessary," he said on US television.
Asked on another channel if he would vote for the proposed plan, his Republican opponent, John McCain, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
"The outline I've read [shows] that this is something we're all going to have to digest and be able to move forward with.
The option of doing nothing is simply not acceptable," he said.
The $700 billion plan aims to buy back with taxpayers' money the bad debts, risky assets and unsellable debts of US financial institutions.
It comes after 14 months of a crisis triggered by the bursting of a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of subprime mortgages before spreading to other more widespread forms of credit securities (ABCP) and leading to a liquidity freeze and the collapse of banks and financial institutions.
It was a group of elected Republicans who had derailed the first draft agreement, last week.
This impasse is believed to have been broken since Democrats accepted that some "toxic" assets of troubled companies should only be insured by the government, rather than bought.
In order to round off the odds for everyone in Congress, a provision was also added stating that if the government had to assume losses for five years with this program, it could implement new taxes to help it recover its stake.
The new plan provides for the payment of a first tranche of 250 billion to which can be added another 100 billion if the president deems it necessary.
The payment of another $350 billion is expected to be approved by another vote in Congress.
In exchange for its help, Washington will obtain stakes in rescued companies that will earn it dividends in case of profit and that it can sell when the turmoil is over.
The federal government will have the ability to delay foreclosure proceedings for homes attached to home loans covered by this plan, as well as set limits on compensation and severance pay to executives of affected companies.
The architects of the plan would like to see it put to a vote in the House of Representatives today, and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite their best efforts, it is not yet certain that their plan will get the green light.
Voices continued to rise yesterday against this project, both in the Republican and Democratic camp.
"Obviously, Washington doesn't hear you," Republican Scott Garrett, a member of the House Finance Committee, told his constituents.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
But not the one of taking advantage of taxpayers."
Leader of a small group in Congress dubbed "the caucus of skeptics," Democratic Representative Brad Sherman presents things differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
"Four hundred eminent professors of economics, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us to tell us: Congress is being asked not to rush and to carefully consider the way forward," he said yesterday.
At the same time, in Europe, there was once again evidence of the global nature of the crisis.
At the end of an emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for 11.2 billion euros (16.3 billion US).
The intervention of the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg was made necessary after the French bank BNP Paribas said it was giving up on acquiring its shipwrecked competitor since it lost 2 billion euros ($2.9 billion) in the subprime mortgage crisis in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is among the twenty largest European banks and the ten largest insurers.
"This is not wasted money," Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos said yesterday.
In exchange, voting rights in the bank and influence are recovered.
This is precisely something that savers and households appreciate now that times are looking uncertain."
Meanwhile, on the other side of the Channel, the British government seemed to be on track to nationalise another bank battered by the financial crisis.
According to the British press, the government would take over all outstanding loans at Bradford and Bringley, including more than 41 billion (75.5 billion US) in mortgages.
Spain's Santander bank said yesterday that it would buy the branches and customer accounts of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley would be the second bank, after Northern Rock, that the British government should nationalize since the beginning of this financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a committed icon
His azure-eyed beauty was for a long time his trump card, some would say his weakness.
Had he freed himself from the narcissistic mirror, the American actor with the charming smile?
Yes and no.
His modesty, sensitivity and a talent that flowed naturally will also have distanced him from the register of power that gives birth to the true sacred monsters.
But what a great long-distance runner!
Paul Newman, who died Friday at the age of 83 from lung cancer on his ranch in Connecticut, remains one of the last icons of American cinema of the boom years.
Less monumental than Brando, to whom he resembled and of whom he was for a long time a kind of rival on the screen, more cautious in his acting, certainly more fragile, but also apostle of freedom and the bursting of dramatic conventions.
Mixed bloods often make beautiful children.
He was born in Ohio in 1925 to a German-Jewish father and a Hungarian-born mother.
From these European roots will be born one of the glorious faces of the American dream.
Without excessive ego, ultimate mark of quality.
Because in him was projected a whole country in love with the self-made man, the fighter of the Pacific War, wounded in combat, who in the early 50s studied drama at Yale and then attended the Actor's Studio in New York, before triumphing in the theater, television, soon in the cinema.
This same man who campaigned for civil rights was also the racing driver who placed second in the 24 Hours of Le Mans in 1979, coupled with a sex symbol, although a member of a model couple formed since 1958 with actress Joanne Woodward.
Also disappear with him the shadows of this secret, discreet, committed star, allergic to the bursts of show business, whose enigma we will not have quite pierced.
An honest man, in the noblest sense of the word.
The death of Paul Newman made moviegoers dizzy this weekend, as his great roles clash on the black screen of memories.
More than half a century of a constantly changing seventh American art parades through him.
Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), the young man rejecting his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on a Hot Roof adapted by Tennessee Williams in 1958, come back to jostle in memory.
Closer to us (1990), we evoke his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled at his old age by a marriage that did not fulfill all its promises.
So many other Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
This boxer Rocky Graziano, delinquent, tormented, violent, unforgettable in Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role intended for James Dean, taken over after his death, who really launched Newman in 1956.
This sympathetic thug in the brilliant The Sting, Oscar for Best Picture in 1973.
Bitter and vengeful billiards player in Robert Rossen's magnificent The Hustler (1961), he reprised the character on the return in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, which earned him his only Oscar out of nine nominations in 1987.
That face through the ages was him.
Him again.
The eras jostle through his career.
Young people know him especially through the cult Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977), in Reggie Dunlop, coach of an unorthodox ice hockey team.
His fans found him in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy by the Coen brothers.
With a final role as the godfather of the Irish mafia in Sam Mendes' Road to Perdition in 2003, the circle was complete.
Unlike several film legends who left the profession early on, Newman remained in the saddle for a long time, while denouncing Hollywood, its gold, its splendour and its concessions.
The French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered, not without humor, "as a living challenge to "underplaying" judging his performances too strong.
The profession has not always been kind to the handsome Paul Newman to whom the roles fell for a long time all cooked in the beak.
However, he played less often the young first than the marginalized: neurotic, alcoholic, bastards or desperate, whose perfect features reflected the excesses and revolts.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known facets of his true modest sensibilities.
His Rachel, Rachel, in 1968 (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), with his wife Joanne Woodward in the lead role, drew a fine female portrait of melancholy.
He who lost his son Scott to an overdose dedicated his film Harry and Son in 1984, a work of modesty and sadness.
Among the rain of tributes that swept over Newman yesterday, his great friend and former comrade-in-arms Robert Redford (they had played together in The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) said, very saddened: "His presence has made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of existence are vibrant traits of the late actor.
Beyond his career as a legend, also fades a great activist for civil rights, ecology, independent cinema, a protester of the excesses of Hollywood.
We will have seen a lot of his doe enthroned on jars of vinaigrette, sauces, cookies and other foods, judging the process of rather bad taste, although gag at first.
The profits from these sales were nevertheless donated to his Foundation for Special Education.
Newman, rather than sitting on his myth, will have committed himself to the end.
He left his five daughters a letter containing these sentences: "Always and until the end, your father was incredibly grateful for his lucky star.
It was a privilege to be there."
And a privilege for us to have followed the career of such a lucid and generous American artist.
Model citizen, in short, and in addition.
What could Zuschlag &amp; Company manufacture in their invoice factory?
Hearings on the ongoing criminal proceedings against János Zuschlag and his accomplices will begin shortly on 8 October.
The politician and his accomplices are accused of fraud, in the form of a criminal organization, on a permanent and regular basis, having caused particularly significant damage. Other charges were brought against them, such as forgery and use of forgery.
According to the prosecutor's office, the money from subsidies was spent for personal purposes, while the services were justified by false invoices.
The money from the state and municipalities, about HUF 65 million in total, went on the one hand into the coffers of the Fiatal Baloldal movement and on the other hand into the pockets of some people.
Their method, also made public by the investigating authorities, was to receive the money from the subsidies obtained by issuing invoices for expenses, behind which no real service was provided and thus, the associations never respected their commitments.
According to the indictment, many of the invoices were fake.
For the latter, they obtained invoice books at the Józsefváros market, while they made the stamps in Kiskunhalas.
For the names of companies that were to appear on the invoices, it was decided, among other things, during the tours in the province of the North of Lake Balaton, carried out by István Lados, at the request of János Zuschlag.
According to the latter's testimony, he had to locate boarding houses and restaurants.
For his personal consumption, he asked for an invoice, on the model of which they made the other bills that they would submit, among others, to the Ministry of Youth and Sports, the Ministry of Social Affairs and Labour, as well as the Municipality of the Capital to access subsidies.
The majority of the invoices were created by István Lados and his accomplice András Őri, who, according to our information, was mainly concerned with drafting the files necessary to obtain the subsidies.
During a "scouting tour", one of Lados' choices was a bistro.
According to the two invoices issued by the Zuschlag in 2003, this place provided the restoration of a group of 90 people, members of the association Biztos Pont Egyesület.
However, according to the manager, it would have been impossible for so many people to occupy this place, at the same time.
Similarly, in the summer of 2002, the invoice drawn up in the name of the Jobb Jövőért Foundation, which would later be called Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért, was teeming with errors of form and substance.
A boarding house, located in Badacsonytomaj, actually had only three rooms, and a maximum of ten people could spend the night there. Yet the invoice mentioned one hundred and thirty customers.
Highly imaginative billers also went to excess, when they mentioned the company Pigal Kft, also belonging to the Horeca sector. In their accounts, neither the name of Jobb Jövőért nor that of the Hoppá appeared, according to information given to the prosecutor's office.
Győző Farkas, the company's manager, told the hvg.hu website that when the prosecutor's office summoned him and showed him the invoices, he knew right away that they were forged documents.
"Our company name and tax number were placed in the wrong place on the stamp."
He added: "Beyond the form, the fact that according to the bill, a hundred people stayed there, did not fit either, since this establishment has only eleven rooms, which do not have as much space.
In addition, the bill also mentions meals, and our restaurant has been closed for a long time."
Zealous billers also did not inquire about Budapest travel agencies, which were part of their choice, but only organized trips abroad. Thus, naively, they indicated stays in Hungary on invoices to be paid in cash, which also goes against the accounting practices of the agency.
In addition, as it appeared during the investigation, they also added VAT on these documents, while services concerning travel activities, whose destination is outside the European Union, are invoiced without VAT.
Similarly, the VAT rate of the four invoices issued in the name of Hotel Révfülöp to the order of Jobb Jövőért was incorrect, since the company's services do not bear a VAT of 25% as indicated, but a VAT of 15%. In addition, hotel employees only issue printed invoices, while fake ones were written by hand.
The Public Prosecutor's investigation reveals that the "issuers" also made mistakes by mentioning as a service the transport of goods by road, which the company issuing the invoices could not carry out, since its profile was investment advice.
In addition, it is also for defects of form, such as inadequate types of invoices and false stamps, that invoices issued to the order of Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, of XXI. Századi Kulturális Egyesület and de Biztos Pont turned out to be false.
Just as in the case of the company Ravenna Bt. or the sports camp of Kunfehértó, both of which deny being the authors of the invoices issued in their name.
Nor did the counterfeiters pay attention to the fact that HIB Kft., established in Nyíregyháza, was in liquidation at the time when (in 2001) Fiatal Városért Egyesület's group was supposed to have a meal at their home. According to our information, it is for this reason that the liquidator of the company denies having issued this invoice.
Deliberately issued invoices
Another category of billers is those who were fully aware that they were being asked to issue fictitious invoices.
The Esély Budapesttért Alapítvány Foundation, at the request of the Fiatal Baloldal - Ifjú Szocialisták group, issued an invoice to the Együtt Foundation in Harmadik Évezredért, for the sum of four million HUF.
According to the indictment, the manager of Collab Kft. was induced to issue false invoices by one of the accused, Ludovic Györfi.
Similarly, the company Biogate Kft., which is currently in liquidation and in 2003, issued invoices to the order of the Jobb Jövőért Alapítvány Foundation, the Atlasz Egyesület Association and the Vörösfenyő Egyesület Association, for an amount of approximately HUF five million, but no service was actually provided.
No financial movement took place either, since the invoices issued were subsequently cancelled, but the organizations avoided mentioning it in their accounts.
The next category of bill-issuing companies is companies directly related to the accused.
Thus, the administrative delegate of the managing director of Delta Trió Kft., dealing with the trade in fuel and motor vehicles, whose registered office was in Budapest but where he could not be found, was Iván Kubatov.
In October, November and December 2005, this company issued several invoices for the sale of computer equipment amounting to approximately HUF 18 million.
According to the investigation, this equipment was purchased by Cash Investment Kft. of Kiskunhalas, which had been in liquidation since 14 September 2005.
The director of that company was a man of Romanian origin, to whom Iván Kubatov also allegedly sent documents relating to the company between 2002 and 2005.
As far as we know, Kubatov admitted during the investigation that he issued invoices to the order of the companies Atlasz, Hoppá and de Együtt a Harmadik Évezredért Alapítvány, and that he pocketed their counter-value.
It was precisely at the request of Iván Kubatov that Romanian masons created the companies Fa-Bani Jos Faipari Kft. and Jos-Investment Bt.
In reality, none of these companies were operating, which the accused explains by the fact that they did not receive work.
He nevertheless made use of these companies, since at the request of Mr. Zsolt Szente, co-accused and draftsman of the deeds of foundation of the societies, he drew up invoices in their names, in the order of associations relating to Zuschlag, such as the associations Atlasz and Y-Generáció.
Kubatov gave organizations a total of 15 invoices, issued by the companies Cash Investment, Delta Trió, Fa-Bani Jos, Jos Investment and Linaxtrade, worth HUF 14.2 million.
The prosecutor's office believed that 10% of the sums indicated on the invoices as well as VAT went into Kubatov's pocket.
The man even used the company Szi-Beri Bt. to draw up fictitious invoices that were used as part of Biztos Pont's grant application.
In January 2006, the Y-Generáció Association and Szövetség a Modern Magyarországért applied for a subsidy from the Socialist Party's charitable body, Táncsics Mihály Alapítvány (TMA).
They obtained this grant for an amount of twice HUF 500,000, but these amounts were not used for the purposes indicated in the application.
To prevent this from being known, five fictitious invoices received from Works Team Kft. were submitted to the TMA.
Moreover, it was these invoices that were found during the search of Árpád Kemecsei's office at the Ministry of Education.
During the hearing, some of the accused will recount the method of manufacturing the invoices, as they had already done before the prosecutor's office previously.
What could be really interesting would be if the main accused, János Zuschlag himself, decides to lift the veil on the whole story.
So far, his confession is not very detailed, and although he has repeatedly promised to tell every detail, he has not yet done so.
The question is whether this is in his interest, or, possibly, the Socialists would have reached an agreement according to which in exchange for the reimbursement of a large part of the fifty million HUF, Zusi would bear the blame alone.
Today, the latter is probably offended, since requests for his placement under house arrest, on the basis of a relaxation of his conditions of detention, continually fall on deaf ears.
While those who have caused much greater damage, and the perpetrators of economic crimes that cannot be repaired, wander freely or at least wait at their own homes for the end of the proceedings. He does not have that possibility.
The psychology of one-upmanship: why do we spend more money?
At auctions, buyers tend to spend more, and overestimate the merchandise.
Neurology and economics researchers at New York University have succeeded in uncovering the neurological and economic basis of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to their study published in the journal Science, human beings do not want to be left behind in this type of competition, such as an auction on eBay, and that is why they even prefer to pay too high a price.
This research attempted to draw up a neurological diagram of this kind of "game" using experimental auctions.
One group of volunteers played lotto, while the other group took part in a playful auction, while using a functional magnetic resonance (fMRI) process, the researchers analyzed the active brain domains of the experimental subjects.
In both games, participants could win money, but during the auction, an essential element of which is the outbidding of a third party, the set under the brainstem, called striatum, would move intensively when the game was lost.
This part of the brain, along with several other functions, plays a role in the nervous system's "self-stimulation" mechanism.
This is why, according to the researchers, the rise in prices is explained by the flight from the violent reaction of the striatum.
In support of their theories, the economist members of this group of researchers pursued analyses of financial supervision.
During these meetings, three groups outbid a partner in various circumstances.
They simply informed the control group of the real value of the product in question, and so they made their bet.
To another group, they promised that if, in addition, they came out on top of the game, then they would receive an additional 15 dollars, as a reward.
While the third group received this $ 15 before the auction, but the members of the group also lost this money, in case they lost the auction.
The difference between these two groups is in fact that the emphasis was on victory in one group, while in the other, on failure.
By proving the neurologists' hypothesis in this way, the members of the team of players "against failure" were willing to bet higher than those made by the control group and the group "for victory".
"These results cannot be demonstrated by any already existing economic theory.
Indeed, each of them explained the phenomena observed during auctions only by the pleasure of winning and the parade in front of the risk.
Only neurological imaging methods have helped to remove the contradiction between the two theories by now leading to a third explanation." - noted Andrew Schotter, professor of the School of Economics of New York University.
Hepatitis: when should we see a doctor?
Worldwide, about half a billion people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, while in Hungary, chronic liver disease is mentioned as one of the leading causes of death.
There are an estimated one hundred thousand patients with the hepatitis virus in Hungary, but only seven thousand are undergoing treatment. This is due to the fact that patients often do not know that they are carriers of the virus.
The name hepatitis is a generic name given to infections affecting the liver and caused by different viruses.
There are many similarities between their symptoms. Inflammation of the liver and jaundice are characteristic, but the pathogens and diseases caused differ from each other.
Hepatitis viruses, depending on the pathogenic genes, spread mainly in two forms: hepatitis A and E through the digestive tract (for example: contaminated food or water), hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses through blood and body fluids (semen, vaginal secretion, saliva).
For travellers, it is recommended to be vaccinated against viruses A and B anyway. There is no vaccine for C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after eating contaminated food, usually accompanied by poor general condition, weakness, stomach upset and nausea.
Then develops on the skin and on the white of the eye a visible jaundice, the stool becomes lighter and the urine takes a darker color. Recovery can take two to three weeks.
Worldwide, every year, one million people die from the most severe form of this disease, such as cancer or cirrhosis of the liver caused by hepatitis B.
The main cause is that, according to estimates, only one in ten patients receives medical treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most patients do not know they have the virus, because the pathogenic gene sneakily destroys liver cells. In many cases, the first symptoms appear only after 20 to 30 years.
Therefore, early prevention is very important, as well as regular screening tests.
Contamination is much higher than average among a population of three groups: people who had a blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and tattooed people.
Currently, there are 200 million patients with chronic hepatitis C worldwide.
Since the disease can be detected by routine laboratory examination, it is advisable to consult your doctor as soon as symptoms of unknown origin are observed.
The disease can be cured, if detected in time. The virus can be eradicated from the body, in this way the risk of contagion disappears and the development of cancer is prevented.
September 30 is World Hepatitis Day, organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing patients from around the world.
Its goal is to draw attention to chronic liver cirrhosis, caused by viruses, the causes of its development and the importance of early diagnosis of the disease.
Benelux governments nationalise part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux states are coming to the aid of the Belgian-Dutch bank, as the first European banking institution in distress following the snowball effect of the credit market crisis in the United States, by partially nationalizing it. The three countries are supporting, to the tune of 11.2 billion euros, this financial and insurance institution also having interests in Hungary.
This weekend, the Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments reached an agreement at the highest level in this case, also appealing to the European Central Bank and the head of competition of the European Commission.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has been deepening for more than a year is for Fortis Bank. From a certain point of view, the decisions that will be made in the case of this bank will serve as a precedent.
In accordance with the decision taken on Sunday night, the three states will buy back nearly half (up to 49%) of the bank's capital located in each country.
The bank will undoubtedly sell part of its shareholdings, including, in the first place, the activities, mainly insurance, which it acquired last year from the Dutch organization ABN Amro.
Last week, Fortis shares began a steep fall. In the second half of the week, serious signs of crisis have already been revealed at the bank.
Analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is far too big to be allowed to fail.
On Friday alone, the company's shares fell 12 percent to its lowest level 14 years ago.
Since January, stocks have fallen by more than two-thirds of their value.
Taking into account the current value of the shares, the total value of the group's capital is around 14 billion euros, which, according to the company's managers, is not realistic.
The company's management blames uncertainty across the Atlantic, in connection with the adoption of the $700 billion US bailout, for the fall in Fortis shares.
On Monday, papers have already benefited from a slight increase.
On Friday, Filip Dierckx was appointed head of the bank, as the new managing director.
The financial institution was also looking for private buyers, but has not yet received a proposal on the merits.
Previously, the Belgian government announced that investors should not worry, they would not lose their money.
No panic was felt in the bank's customer circle and no branch was stormed.
In Hungary, Fortis has independent agencies and has also acquired leasing companies.
Does the one who believes in God feel less pain?
According to the results of recent research, religious belief functions as a kind of analgesic, which has already helped to make the death of Catholic martyrs more bearable.
The British newspaper Telegraph published an article according to which researchers from the University of Oxford carried out an interesting experiment by analyzing at what level belief in God can influence human tolerance for pain.
In this bizarre experiment, 12 Catholic believers and as many atheists were subjected to electric shocks, while each of them observed a painting representing the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude much of the suffering.
Through a technique of palpation of the human brain, it has also been discovered that Catholics have been able to activate the part of their brain responsible for regulating pain.
This analysis is the first of a series of experiments, in which academics, scholars, philosophers and theologians participate from different sectors of the university.
More precisely, the experiment is conducted as follows: an instrument emitting sparks and scattering electroshocks is attached to the left hand of the experimental subject.
The researchers asked participants in the experiment to look closely at two paintings, one being the Virgin Mary painted by Sassoferrato in the 17th century and the other, the Lady with the Ermine painted by Leonardo da Vinci in the 15th century.
The researchers behind this experiment hoped that the sight of the Virgin Mary evokes some kind of state of faith among believers, while the choice of Da Vinci's painting, not very different from the first, focused on its calming effect.
The experimental subjects spent half an hour in an MRI scanner, and during this time received 20 electroshocks in four parts in succession, while looking at either the religious-themed painting or the more general themed one.
Catholics said that at the sight of the Virgin Mary, they felt like they were "safe," like someone who is "taken care of" and they "calmed down, and peace invaded them."
At the sight of the painting of religious theme, they reported 12% less pain than when they looked at Leonardo's work.
The psychologist Miguel Farias, who himself took part in the experiment, believes that the same effects can be achieved with any other strong image, in atheists, provided you find the appropriate photo.
"We should find an image to which they react very positively, such as a mother or father," the psychologist said.
Tom Wright, Anglican bishop, welcomed the results of the research.
"The practice of faith should change and in many cases, actually change our personality," Wright added.
After these excellent results, the only question remains as to what effect would be the effect on the pain regulation of the subjects if believers were shown a Madonna painted by Leonardo or by a painter of the same caliber?
Would seeing a better quality Virgin Mary lead to better results?
You are what you disclose about yourself
On the occasion of its tenth anniversary, Google claims that it can be found deep in people's pockets just like the sky above their heads. He knows where they spent their holidays, which specialists they consult and what their interests are.
But that's still not enough, according to Eric Schmidt, who is one of the company's influential people.
While skeptics draw a parallel with Orwell's vision of horror, they do not see the essence of Web 2.0.
Eric Schmidt recently told the Financial Times that Google's main ambition is to gather even more information about its users. This is necessary so that the founders of Google can respect their initial goal which sounded like this: "Let's collect in one system all the information in the world!".
According to the Google executive interviewed, after ten years of global upheaval, they are still only at the beginning of their goals of being able to process all information.
To the question: what will be in five years? Schmidt replied that he would like Google to be able to answer questions like "What could I do tomorrow?" or "What job would work best for me?" However, software will only be able to answer this kind of question, simple at first glance, the day it knows enough about users.
It is not perfectly clear to all Internet users that the words used during Internet searches, the IP address of the computer initiating the search and the pages subsequently consulted by interested persons are precisely listed.
Through the Personalized Search program launched two years ago, users can, for example, store their own search history and can see what they searched for, what they clicked on. Thanks to this, in the long term, Recommendations, a program based on the same logic, will be able to give much more personalized answers, and will submit products and services to us based on our previous statements and saved preferences.
What happens if someone uses my data against me, if they look at what my work is? ask users, who are concerned about Google's monopoly of information.
In most cases, it is the potential power represented by society that can arouse fear, and it is not remorse, fear of punishment, desire for freedom or possibly revolt against power that can provoke a counter-reaction in Internet users.
However, it is a confirmed fact that the search terms are not only recorded, but in justified cases they are transmitted to a third party, and in this kind of legal case, nothing protects the personal rights of Internet users.
Perhaps the most high-profile example in recent times is the coordinated action against Brazilian pedophiles, during which Google passed on to the Brazilian government the information it had gathered from the public page called Orkut, allowing identification.
Human rights-conscious netizens breathed a sigh of relief last May, when Google, arm in arm with electronic legal protection agency EFF, proved its right in court against the FBI. According to the ruling, in the future, Google will still not be able to be compelled by any of the constitution's points to disclose information about the FBI's secret request of any kind.
(At the same time, the federal government successfully obtained some 50,000 web addresses and 1,000 search terms that it had won over the strengthening of the Child Protection Act, passed several years earlier. But in the end, he failed to obtain the lists of private users' searches, nor the entire list of websites and keywords from the last two months.)
Google's judgment is therefore quite contradictory: it is castigated by those who fear the transmission of their personal data, because they think that their intimate sphere and private domain suffer when they start using Google services. As a result, they are attacking them in the spirit of revolt against multinational corporations that are proud of their conservative image.
Meanwhile, American geek culture and its "wildlings" of enthusiasts, activists and enthusiastic computer users who appear in many countries see Google as the next generation of big business, the "hip corporation", as opposed to its rival, Microsoft, labeled as an invader of the world because of Windows.  even if both are fighting for the same goal.
This can be explained by the fact that Google, unlike Microsoft, does not ask its users for identification code, does not ask for money for its applications. The documentary code and the package of programs, continuously refreshed, has a much more accessible, younger and cooler effect, compared to the practice of the official software giant.
The reason may also be that geeks see exactly the problematic relationship between human rights and the internet, and what Web 2.0, the most proclaimed key word in recent years, pulls behind it.
Indeed, Web 2.0 is not about anything other than collaboration, the fact that we intentionally leave traces behind, and that we use the communication channels at our disposal, and while the dimension of these changes one by one, the essential remains the same: we expose ourselves.
A young person, in general, can keep a profile on several public pages, from Facebook to Xanga, and he can even link them to other performances, such as Twinter, or last.fm, listing his musical habits. Then, it can link these to a tracking system, such as FriendFeed or Blip.fm. These young people can also keep blogs, where their most recent photo galleries automatically appear that they store on Flickr or Picasa.
While we can read many examples, such as that of the girlfriend who easily understands from the morning photos, taken by the circle of mutual friends, with whom her unfaithful friend spent the evening, or that of the company that fired one of its employees, just for the sincere opinions that he wrote on his blog about top management,  We can be sure of one thing: the term privacy is totally to be reconsidered nowadays.
The one who lives an online life, is made up of what he shows of himself, and this is how we can define the principle behind the behavior of today's young people.
Whoever wants to hide something, or at least, wants to try to circumvent Google's monopoly, can do so (starting, for example, with Scroogle, using the Google search system, but, at the same time, intentionally leaving no trace).
The number of people who deliberately do not register on public pages so that it is not possible to find them, is not the least. Google online services, from word processing to image processing, reading information can be replaced by alternative versions, which are not attached to huge server farms and which do not assemble our best profile, having existed until now.
Public opinion is waiting, without really hiding it, for the moment when Google will reveal its true nature.
The company, with its current value of $156 billion, is worth more than IBM ($140 billion), Intel ($124 billion) or Coca-Cola ($110 billion). The AdWords/AdSense advertising domains threaten the turnover of advertising agencies, while the services introduced at an increasingly rapid pace cause serious headaches not only for Microsoft, but for many other creators of computer programs.
However, critical observers find, alongside all this, contradictions with worrying effects: for example, the top management of the company refused, in its entirety, the protests of the employees, after it doubled the price of the company kindergarten and after the company deemed the daily multiple catering too expensive,  taken at any time. All this seems ridiculous compared to the fact that already in 2006, Google acquiesced to the Chinese government and according to the terms of their agreement, the company detects all the results that hurt good taste, as well as the interests of the Chinese regime.
According to one of the company's internal rules, new services are not announced only when they can be used. What is certain is that in the coming months and years, they will move the world on new points. While some think that Google's book and magazine scanning and archiving project is taking on such dimensions that the company will soon find itself facing the Supreme Court of the United States, others tremble in front of its Health system, because in it, we can build a complete medical profit from our results of previous analyzes,  our doctors and our problems.
The fact that Google is building a genetic database can give good raw material for the next generation of science fiction authors. The novel by the famous Cory Doctorow, written with Orwellian semitones, describes the future in which a man could be approached in a frightening way just through Google's data.
