Warsaw Stock Exchange makes proposal for purchase of Prague Stock Exchange
The Warsaw Stock Exchange has offered two hundred million euros, about five billion Czech crowns, for the purchase of 100% of the package of shares of the Prague Stock Exchange.
Ludwik Sobolewski, the president of the Warsaw Stock Exchange, confirmed this proposal, which the Poles made despite the fact that, previously, the Czechs had excluded the Warsaw Stock Exchange from the circle of potential new owners of the Prague Stock Exchange.
The reason for this exclusion is that the Warsaw Stock Exchange is in the hands of the State.
99% of the shares are in the hands of the Polish State, which wants to divest itself of more than 60% of its shares in a few months of activity.
According to the Czech business daily E15, the Polish proposal represents the highest bid so far for the takeover of the Prague Stock Exchange.
According to the Czech press, the Vienna Stock Exchange, the transatlantic Nasdaq Stock Exchange, the New York Stock Exchange, the London Stock Exchange and Deutsche Börse have made an offer so far.
Petr Koblic, the head of the Prague Stock Exchange, said last week that among those interested, the Warsaw Stock Exchange would be the least good new owner, and did not rule out the fact that this could lead to the demise of the Prague Stock Exchange in the future.
The value of the Prague Stock Exchange is estimated at between 5 and 10 billion Czech crowns by market specialists.
On the basis of an agreement between the shareholders, some 90% of the papers would be sold.
The largest owner of the Prague Stock Exchange is the investment bank Patria Finance, with about 25 per cent of shareholdings, followed by 14.7 per cent of Ceská Sporitelna Bank and Tiger Holding Four S. a.r.l. with 13.5 per cent.
