The intelligent automobile mimics the flight of the bumblebee
What method would be better for developing technologies that can avoid an obstacle, if not the imitation of an obstacle detector already existing in nature?
Like for example, that of bees.
In the amazing project presented at CEATEC, taking place in Japan, buzzing bees gave Nissan engineers the starting strategic idea, to inspire them on how to design the next generation of obstacle detectors.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan built a mini robot car, a bio-inspired self-robotic control system of the BR23C type, which it equipped with the qualities of bees, the ultimate goal being to encourage the development of a system capable of avoiding all obstacles.
During its flights, each bee forms its own oval-shaped space, which in reality looks a lot like our secure protective shell - explained Kazuhhiro Doi, director of the brand's research and development and technological public relations department, at the exhibition.
The faceted eye of the bee plays a key role, since it is able to see in all directions, at an angle of 300 degrees.
To mimic the functions of the faceted eye, engineers approached the idea of the laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles at an angle of 180 degrees and at a distance of 2 meters in front of the BR23C, evaluates distances and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which transforms it into an evasive maneuver right away.
The perception of the obstacle takes place in a fraction of a second. Then, the mini auto robot, imitating the movements of the bee, immediately changes the direction of its wheels by turning it at an angle sufficient to avoid collision.
Unlike any system that exists today, this evasive maneuver is entirely instinctive.
"If this were not the case, the mini robot car would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid the obstacle" - explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the robotic car project.
It must react instinctively and instantaneously, since this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable and innermost layer of the protective envelope, a layer where for the moment collision is considered inevitable.
This whole process should reflect what the bee does to avoid other bees.
The process should take place in the blink of an eye.
Unlike bees, the difference cannot go upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional, and only in the direction in which the wheels can turn.
In this way, instead of the infinite combinations that bees have to avoid other bees, in our case, we could only use rotary movement, acceleration and slowing down as maneuvers available to the mini auto robot.
The BR23C uses lithium polymer batteries that are lighter and have a greater energy concentration, making their life longer than in the lithium-ion version.
According to Andoh, it is the instinctive intelligent reaction that is paramount, not the processing of the data, let alone the ability to store.
This mechanism should only process and react to a few incoming signals per second.
There is no need to store them and react with intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers. This way, it only uses a few dozen kilobytes of continuous memory.
You don't need memory with a capacity of gigabytes, or even megabytes.
This is the first step towards designing technology for instant avoidance. According to Nissan estimates, this system will make its way into mass-produced cars in the next ten years.
Another application could be its incorporation into the GPS satellite navigation system, so that it can guide the driver to his destination avoiding obstacles in his path.
We even gave the expensive baby a name
The written version of the $700 billion economic rescue plan, aimed at buying up bad loans from banks, and to be used in installments, is ready.
In the first round, half of this amount will be spent.
Reuters reports that in new debates extending until after midnight on Saturday, local East Coast time, congressional leaders have agreed on the controversies that have existed for days and days, around the rescue plan totaling $ 700 billion.
"We have taken a serious step forward" - said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic speaker of the US House of Representatives, according to which it remains only to put the agreements on paper.
The compromise, born from the plan, is supported by the two presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said commenting on the results of the compromise that the program will work and be effective, but more needs to be implemented. According to Pelosi, this is not about rescuing Wall Street, but about turning the wheels of the economy the other way.
The written version of the plan was made public before Asian markets opened Sunday night at 8 p.m. Washington local time (i.e. Monday at 2 a.m., according to Central European local time), but did not cause a dramatic rise in the stock markets.
On Monday, the House of Representatives will be the first to vote on the bill called the Emergency Economic Stabilization Act of 2008. Then his fate will be in the hands of the Senate.
On Saturday night, President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi, and then the White House also welcomed the news of the deal.
"We are pleased with the progress achieved last night, and we highly appreciate the efforts of both parties to stabilize our financial markets and to protect our economy," said Tony Fratto, White House spokesman.
Moreover, the program diverges from the Bush administration's initial proposal that the $700 billion should be spent at one time on the purchase of securities relating to bad credits.
From now on, a maximum of half of the sum of 700 billion can be spent. The first $250 billion will be delivered immediately after Congress passes the law, likely on Monday. This first sum will be used by the Secretary of the Treasury to buy bad loans from the banks, while the use of the additional $100 billion will be left to the discretion of the President.
The program will be overseen by an independent body, in which the chairman of the Federal Reserve will also participate.
The spending of the second half of the $700 billion depends on a new congressional decree.
Under the Act, the Treasury Secretariat will be able to implement a combined strategy: it will be able to purchase bad debts, mortgages and bad mortgages, and other types of "toxic" debts at the same time.
The appropriate people in the department have stated that buybacks can take place through an auction, but also directly.
The rule gives the companies concerned the opportunity to take part in an insurance program, where the Treasury Secretariat guarantees the tools that cause the concerns, for which the companies will have paid a premium equivalent to the foreseeable damage.
Paulson said the law provides the tools to spend $700 billion on the urgent needs of the financial system, whether it's the vast buyback of bad loans, their insurance, or avoiding the risk of the system leading to the collapse of one major financial institution.
"We will take the necessary steps, to be ready for the application of the law, as soon as it is signed" - he added.
On the other hand, bank executives who are in bad shape and waiting for state aid can expect that their severance packages, simply called golden parachute across the Atlantic, will be capped by the government.
Wage caps are mentioned only in specific cases. In addition, the limitations depend on how the Treasury Secretariat offers its assistance to the company.
The capping principle means that if the Treasury buys back at an auction, they will levy a surplus tax on the golden parachute, unless the discredited bank president retires.
Directly after the bad debt buys out, the government will intervene aggressively to ensure that the amount paid to executives is not exaggerated.
For the image to be complete, it must still be added that the existing golden parachutes are not modified. The cap only concerns new contracts, in order to motivate participation in the plan.
This is the first time in the history of the United States that legal caps will be in place on the salaries of chief executives - commented the chairman of the committee in charge of financial benefits of the House of Representatives, the Democrat Barney Frank.
In addition, the State acquires a right to acquire shares in the banks participating in the plan. In this way, the risk of taxpayers decreases, since they can even be a winner in the deal as soon as the economy and with it the rescued banks fall back on their feet.
The bill mentions that within five years, the President must submit a proposal to Congress that will rule on how losses will be returned to taxpayers from the financial sector.
On both sides, of course, there were those who expressed their doubts about this plan.
That's not why American citizens mandated us, this doesn't protect taxpayer dollars – said California Republican Congressman Darrell Issa.
Her fellow Ohio Democrat, Mary Kaptur, thinks it's the same people who are pressing for action, as those responsible for the Wall Street collapse.
Industrial prices continued to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial selling prices increased by 0.1 per cent compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 per cent compared to August 2007 - reports the Central Statistical Office of Hungary.
Industrial export selling prices increased by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008, while compared to a year earlier, they decreased by 3.9 per cent.
As a result of fluctuations in domestic and export prices, industrial producer prices rose 0.7 per cent over the previous month, and 3.2 per cent over the previous year.
Domestic industrial selling prices rose only to a lesser extent: by 0.1 per cent, compared with the previous month.
Domestic selling prices in the processing industry sectors rose only marginally by 0.1% compared to July.
In August 2008, the most significant price increase was observed in the leather goods and footwear manufacturing sector (2.8 per cent), led by the manufacture of bags and belts with a monthly increase of 4.6 per cent, followed by footwear production with a 2.5 per cent monthly increase.
Higher prices for plastic and chemical raw materials resulted in a considerable monthly increase in prices in the chemical products and materials manufacturing sector (1.6 per cent).
This resulted in deflation in petroleum processing (1.4%), electrical machinery and appliance manufacturing (0.9%), and minimal increase in wood processing (0.1%).
Prices for paper production, publishing and printing have not changed.
Other sectors of the processing industry recorded an increase of between 0.2% and 0.9%.
In the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors, which account for a significant share of domestic industrial exploitation, prices rose by 0.3% in August, mainly due to the effect of the increase in gas prices introduced by the authorities since 1 July.
In a twelve-month comparison, taking into account domestic sales in the processing sectors, prices in the oil processing sector rose the most significantly (32.4 per cent).
In the metallurgical products manufacturing sector, prices increased by 13.2%, while in the important area of food, beverage and tobacco production, prices increased by 11%.
Price decreases occurred in the textile and textile products production (2.5 per cent) and the manufacture of machinery and electrical appliances (0.3 per cent).
In the other sectors of the processing industry, price increases ranged from 0.6% to 9.1%.
In the processing industry as a whole, prices increased by 10.2 per cent over the past year.
Prices in the electricity, gas, steam and water supply sectors were 18.7% higher than in the previous year.
Among the internal trade groups and by sector allocation, in August, the sectors that initiated investment profit showed the most significant monthly price increase (0.7 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, while those in the energy and materials for further processing sectors were unchanged from the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the largest increase was observed in the energy and materials for further processing sectors (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods production sectors, inflation was measured at 6.8 per cent, while for profit-making sectors, a decrease of 1.4 per cent.
Export selling prices in the industrial sector, in HUF, rose 1.1 percent in August from the previous month, while they fell 3.9 percent year-on-year.
In one month, our national means of payment weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro, and by 7.1 percent against the dollar. Compared to August 2007, it strengthened by 7.5 per cent against the euro and 15.9 per cent against the dollar.
