A fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurance companies frequently refuse to sign an insurance contract with a candidate, based on information about their drug purchases.
Information protection experts fear that the data market is spiralling out of control.
"There are data protection programs that link the use of information regarding the prescription of medicines, in all cases, to the consent of the data subject.
This kind of program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting your chicken coop to a fox" - recalled Richard Dicket, the creator of the program used to manage drug prescriptions, to the Washington Post.
Insurance companies make the insurance premium and the insured capital in case of damage depend on the state of health of the customer who presents himself, and if they consider that the risk is too great, they do not even insure him.
In the past, they sent candidates for a medical examination, and they only signed insurance contracts with them after they had seen the results.
For ten years, Dick has found a much cheaper procedure: from an identification number, he easily obtains from pharmacies, the data concerning the person's purchases of medicines in the past eighteen months. From this, the program determines itself, what disease the person suffers from and what is his state of health.
For example, if this person regularly buys high doses of cholesterol reducer, this refers to an extremely high level of fat in the blood, which immediately puts them in a higher risk category.
Several versions of this program are in circulation. Some determine at the same time a risk coefficient, so there is not much left for the insurer to do except paperwork. However, tiny problems may still appear.
Among the disadvantages of this program is the fact that a drug can be used for different purposes. For example, some mixtures can be used against migraine or hot flashes, but can also be effective against depression.
The latter is considered by insurers as an aggravating risk factor, while the others, not.
Companies have developed in research and data analysis. They must ask the patient for permission before collecting the necessary information from the pharmacy.
They are now forced to do so by the authorities, even if they have not been punished for their shortcomings in the past.
Recently, some companies have also been processing laboratory test results and linking them with drug consumption data. In this way, they are able to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health status.
More and more companies have access to data, and controlling usage is becoming increasingly difficult at the same time.
There is a separate law on the protection of medical data, but its scope extends only to practitioners and insurers.
A bill to expand the circle of control of authorities over companies specializing in the provision of data is currently before Congress.
Dick Richard acknowledges that this is not enough and that is why he has further developed his program, which would condition the transmission of data to the exclusive consent of the data subject.
It is another question of whether the person concerned is really free to give his consent or not, since if he refuses, the insurance companies do not sign an insurance contract with him.
Thus, and ultimately, chickens depend on the benevolence of the fox.
