Mp3 player pointed out, they put hearing at risk.
Listening to music at full volume for an extended period of time using portable music devices such as Mp3 players, can cause permanent damage to hearing.
This is announced by the European Commission, which, in a press release issued in Brussels, quotes the opinion of the Scientific Committee, on the unforeseen and recently identified health risks (Csrseri) of the EU, published today.
"From this scientific report - we read in the note - it appears that 5-10% of those who, for a period of at least 5 years, listen to music at full volume using portable music devices, for more than one hour a day and a week, are at risk of permanent hearing loss."
"I am concerned that such a large number of young people, who frequently use portable music devices and mobile phones at full volume, may unconsciously damage their hearing beyond repair," says Meglena Kuneva.
"According to the scientific data," continues the EU official, "this is a clear risk and we must react quickly.
What matters most is to educate consumers and make this information public domain.
We also need to review existing control systems based on scientific opinion so that they are fully effective and can keep up with new technologies."
Brussels has asked the Independent Scientific Committee to examine the problem, given the intensive use of portable music devices and the increase in the number of young people exposed to the noise they generate.
"The scientists confirm that there are good reasons for concern, and that the European Commission will now examine with member states and other interested parties, what measures, if any, could be adopted to better protect children and young people from exposure to noise from portable and similar music devices.
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable music devices to 100Db, but there is growing concern about hearing damage that could result from excessive exposure to such noise sources.
This data can be well limited using solutions such as reducing noise levels and duration.
The EU Scientific Committee notes that users of portable music devices, who listen to music at full volume (more than 89 decibels) for 5 hours per week, exceed the current limits on the maximum noise level allowed in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for prolonged periods, risk permanent hearing loss after 5 years.
This is of interest to 5-10% of the users of these devices, and their number can be quantified at around 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
