Today, the biggest snag in American journalism lies between who runs the newsrooms—that is, the directors—and the reporters who work for them.
56% of directors at the national level are convinced that reporters share their values, while at the local level, this percentage drops to 23%.
For some, this is linked to "occupational safety".
Managers who expect to lose their job within 3 years are 47% nationally.
As far as journalists are concerned, we go to 30%.
That of "safe work" at the staff level (our editors, editor's note) in America is still on the agenda.
Only 13% of journalists work under contract.
In a huge nation like the USA, with 300 million inhabitants and thousands of journalists, magazines, radio, TV and the Internet, employers often offer what they want, and it quickly becomes a matter of take it or leave it.
Directors almost always receive large salaries, while the editor can earn $10,000 a month, in addition to retirement and insurance payments.
As for holidays, the logic becomes complicated: x days after the first year, x days after the third, up to 15 days in all, passed a certain number of years.
But, according to their revelations, American journalists are often "sick" during the year.
