Elites in danger.
The phenomenon had already manifested itself a few days ago, with the vote of the House of Representatives, contrary to the rescue plan of $ 700 billion approved by the White House: a good significant number of Americans were, and still are, more interested in punishing Wall Street than in saving the American economy.
And it is yesterday's New York Times that confirms it to us communicating that the current crisis divides the Republican Party, even more divided between its old East Coast soul, moderate, favorable to federal institutions as well as the business community, and its new soul, on the contrary, conservative, hostile to "those of Washington" and the world of finance,  powerful especially in the central and southern states.
The soul, precisely, that was felt in a despotic way with the vote I was talking about at the beginning.
However, what has just been mentioned is only an example of the changes, the great changes that the current economic earthquake pre-announces or already allows: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and perhaps not only here.
In the United States as in Europe, the crisis seems to accelerate the phenomena that have been brewing for some time, to such an extent that, in the new climate, they are solidifying and revealing themselves.
The first of these phenomena is the updating, the extraordinary revival, of the dual state-sovereign category, in relation to a kind of renationalization of the economy.
The crisis, in fact, is a crisis of banking-financial institutions that obviously have close foreign relations, but which, above all, are involved on a large scale, the balance sheets of people and families who live in a single country, in a single state.
This immediately creates a political problem for those who govern it: that is, as responding to the difficulties and protests of individuals and families who are also an electorate.
In short, the crisis appears economically global, but politically, it is almost only national here.
Political internationalisation really seems out of the game or has little to say: the clear proof is provided to us by the European Union which, divided as usual, between the various interests and between the various national strategies, is unable to decide on any common political line.
And so, it is from the government of each State that everyone expects interventions, rescue and recovery plans, new rules, and above all an allocation of credits: when we go through a difficult period, only the States possess the economic resources, the mass of financial resources capable of trying to put things back in place.
They also have the necessary means and the legitimacy to use them: two invaluable resources, elements that no market or international organization will ever have at their disposal in a similar way.
This new emphasis on the nation-state crisis is, moreover, in perfect harmony with the still major importance that more recent economic developments in the economy tend to attribute to a factor quite related to this element: territoriality.
. Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had now entered the realm of the network, of ever more sophisticated technology, of non-material, convinced that globalized finance was now destined to dominate the world, we realized all at once, that our future will have to settle accounts more and more with things that are not very material such as water,  crops, oil.
Things that can certainly be transported from one place to another on earth, but which are absolutely linked to a circumscribed space, to a territory.
Thus, who is sovereign, certainly has more cards than one who is not, that is, he who has the misfortune to live in a place without harvest, without oil and without water.
I now come to the second novelty which, however, provides for a fracture.
Who says Territory, State, Government, inevitably says Politics, and therefore Leadership.
In this respect, the economic crisis seems to produce two converging phenomena.
On the one hand, the awareness of the objective need for authoritarian leadership, the search for a person who knows how to take charge of the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discredit for the existing leaderships, economic species that have proved inadequate and full of gray areas.
And moreover, something even deeper, in a certain sense, even disturbing: a discredit, a suffering, an image of inadequacy, a feeling of estrangement that tends to involve the entire class of directors in a growing number of Western countries.
Thus increases even more the conviction of the various classes, before the actions are the same ideas of the social elites until now at their peak, their way of listening and being, their culture in the complex acceptance of the term, to have the same time, and to be ever more alien to the opinions of the majorities.
In short, the demand for leadership feeds underground, a powerful and ramified movement of delegitimization of the ruling classes and traditional political orders, which manifests itself in the improvised electoral "revolts" or, in the collective changes of moods of recent times, from the conservative rise in Austria Bavaria, to the fall of Labour in Great Britain,  to the rebellion of the American congressmen against Bush (and it may well be that the victory of the right in Italy did not happen by chance).
One has the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their rites, their newspapers, their accredited intellectuals, their format, someone would say, have more and more difficulty, which is not new, to understand and therefore to represent the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis reinforces, increases and potentially agitates disproportionately.
In view of all this, to speak of a current "rebellion of the masses" on the agenda, seems frankly exaggerated.
But we say, keep your eyes wide open, this is not without reason.
The super glue to walk on walls.
Defeat the laws of gravity with a super glue and, in the future, walk on walls like Spiderman.
This is the goal of various American research centers, and today, a team of four institutes has almost succeeded.
With an adhesive measuring just 2.5 square centimeters, the researchers managed to keep a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall.
The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers from the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, invented by the team of researchers, is an evolution of those we know that use a particular structure of carbon, called carbon nanotubes.
"The principle of glue can be imagined as a series of tubes arranged like a pile of spaghetti." Explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the legs of geckos, covered with microscopic hairs that ensure the animal a perfect adherent.
Tests on various materials, such as glass, Teflon, and sandpaper, have shown that the new adhesive is ten times stronger than the legs of these reptiles, and at the same time, that it "detaches easily from the wall," says Liming Dai, a researcher in the University of Dayton's School of Engineering.
WALKING ON WALLS? "This material could be used as a temporary adhesive," adds Liming Dai.
Maybe to walk on the walls like Spiderman? Maybe so, but researchers are thinking of a much less fascinating use such as the connection between electronic devices, since carbon nanotubes are conductive of heat and electric current.
Other applications could be in aerospace engineering.
For now, no superheroes.
THE OTHER IS ALSO LOOKING FOR A NEW ADHESIVE.
In an article in the American journal American Chemical Society, the Californian researchers presented an adhesive formed of microfibers like hair, which self-cleans dust during movement on a surface to ensure perfect and constant adhesion.
Medicines: never with fruit juices.
Beware of grapefruit, orange and apple juice.
These drinks, consumed especially in summer because thirst-quenching and rich in vitamins, if associated with certain vital drugs, alter their absorption amplifying or decreasing depending on the case, their effectiveness, with even serious consequences for health.
David Nailey, professor at the University of Western Ontario in London, recalls the risks of fruit juices, whether canned or fresh, if associated with the ingestion of certain drugs; During the 236th national meeting of the American Chemical Society underway in Philadelphia, he sounded a new alarm: all it took is a glass of grapefruit, orange and apple juice to reduce the absorption of certain vital drugs, cancelling out their beneficial effects and putting patients' health at risk.
Grapefruit juice has already been heavily criticized for being held responsible for increasing the effects of certain antiarrhythmic, antibiotic, anxiolytic, antistaminal and neurological drugs, to toxic levels.
RISKY DRUGS - It was the Italian Medicines Agency itself, which had given the news in a newsletter dated two years ago, warning doctors and patients not to underestimate the danger deriving from this mix and to be careful what one drinks, if one takes drugs such as, for example,  Diazepam or Methadone.
NOT JUST GRAPEFRUIT- According to experts, even orange and apple juice contains substances that inhibit drugs.
Long is the list of active ingredients inhibited by grapefruit and other juices.
From there, the appeal of Michele Carruba, director of the Department of Pharmacology of the Public University of Milan: "These discoveries are in general, immediately reported to the various national and international drug agencies that will have to change the informative notes of the drugs if necessary.
It is always advisable to read the illustrative papers of the drugs you are taking, and, if something is not clear, not to be impressed, but to speak clearly to the doctor or pharmacist," the expert told Ansa.
The Nobel Prize in Economics to Paul Krugman.
The Nobel Prize in Economics was awarded to the American Paul Krugman for his research on business models and the location of economic activities.
Krugman, 55, is a neo-Keynesian who teaches at Princeton University and is also a well-known New York Times columnist.
Krugman is one of the greatest critics of the Bush administration's economic and foreign policy solutions.
A few months after the attacks of September 2001, during the days of Enron's bankruptcy, Krugman wrote, in an article published on the New York Times, that the second event would have been more decisive than the first, in terms of consequences on the history of the United States.
A forecast that unleashed many controversies, and which was reproached to the economist for years, but which has now proved accurate.
"I am surprised and even a little shocked at how quickly the memory of scandals such as the collapse of Enron or Worldcom disappeared from public attention," Krugman said in late 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the European Central Bank's executive committee, Krugman is a "valuable economist," but also a "very aggressive" whistleblower, particularly critical of the Bush administration's liberalism excesses.
Open Office, here is the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package
It's the day of the release of OpenOffice.org.3.0, the open source suite of personal productivity that aims to reach more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, offering a free alternative to the most famous Microsoft Office.
Following almost a year's work, carried out by volunteer developers, monitored by SUN Microsystem, the new Open Office package is shown to the general public with various new features: from the welcome screen, and the interface revised and become less austere, to others more important, such as the compatibility born for the operating system Apple Mac OS X,  and support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2, the latest ISO standard version.
Open Office has paid particular attention to the interaction with the 2007 Office suite, and it is indeed possible to open documents with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx.)
Also interesting are some functions specific to certain modules, such as the one that reduces the dimensions of PowerPoint presentations, useful for example, to send them by e-mail, or to import PDF files into the graphic development module, preserving the original appearance of the page.
Also on this front, it is possible to create "hybrid PDF" documents that unite the typical graphic of the Adobe format with the elements of a spreadsheet or text developer.
The collaboration between several people is an element that has had various improvements within the applications: in the spreadsheet, various users can intervene, avoiding conflicts on changes, in the elaboration of texts, since each collaborator is assigned a color of comments for better recognition in the revision phase.
Some companies are even working to bring some OpenOffice functions to the web, and in the coming weeks they should issue the final result.
The Italian version can be downloaded at the http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.htmlet address and is in addition to the English version that was on the mirror since Friday.
Besides Windows and Mac OS, the suite is as usual available additionally, for the Linux operating system.
On request, the installation CD can be shipped to your home or workplace.
And if the theme of free access can be a way to spread it in homes, it is precisely in business, that Open Office the suite tries the great challenge, already being able to count on various projects carried out in the public administration and schools.
Not to mention the realities that offer a training, consultation and assistance service, ideal for small and medium-sized businesses, which could also open up to business prospectives.
Open Office consists of five main modules: Writer, for video writing equivalent to Word; Calc, is the worksheet that aims to replace Excel; Impress, for PowerPoint rival presentations ;D base, such as the famous Access, is the program that allows you to work on databases; finally Drwa is the graphics module.
Goal for 2008, to reach 5 million downloads, and considering that today there are almost 3 million and 600 thousand, it is likely that with the release of the new version, we can even exceed the planned figure
Kohl too, is positive, this is the fourth case of doping.
New case of positivity at the last Tour de France: it is the Austrian of the Gerolsteiner team, Bernhard Kohl, qualified third, and winner of the jersey of the best climber.
It is the website of the daily L'Equipe that reports the news.
At 26, Kohl is the fourth positive cyclist at Cera, the third-generation Epo, after Italians Riccardo Riccò and Leonardo Piepoli, and German Stefan Schumacher, also from Gerolsteiner.
The blood tests carried out on Kohl's test tubes are part of those carried out in recent weeks by the Lausanne and Chatenay-Malabry laboratories.
If the counter-analyses confirm the positivity at Cera, the Austrian will lose his third place in the Tour and will necessarily have to expect two years of elimination.
The news of Kohl's third-generation Epo positivity was confirmed by the head of the French anti-doping agency, Pierre Bordry, who told The Associated Press that he had notified Austrian authorities of the positivity.
The 26-year-old Austrian placed on the podium behind Spain's Carlos Sastre and American Cadel Evans, taking the polka dot jersey for the best climber.
