Found the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fosset, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris was found on a plateau at 3,000 meters above sea level, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammonth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, however, no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson dismissed any remaining doubts: "The plane has been located, we have sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is the one Steve Fosset was traveling on the day he disappeared," he said at a press conference.
The sheriff said no human remains were found on the plane or in the vicinity.
In February, the 63-year-old billionaire was considered dead.
The U.S. Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) said that a few hours after the location of the wreckage, a team of investigators sent to the scene, identified the aircraft: it is indeed the Bellanca 8kcab, disappeared on September 3, 2007, when Fosset took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fosset's personal belongings were found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents bearing Fosset's name, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a sweater.
The search for Fossett was halted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned himself a place in history thanks to a long series of records.
On the sixth attempt, he became in 2002, the first man to complete the circumnavigation of the world on an aerostatic balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he had flown around the world non-stop.
Among all these records, also that of having flown at 15,445 meters high, on the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
