Students victims of expensive rents, up to 900 euros for a room.
The student rental market is not experiencing a crisis
According to the latest survey by Sunia, the tenants' union, renting a single room can cost a student, up to 900 euros in Milan, 700 in Florence, 650 in Naples, 600 in Rome.
"The phenomenon has now reached very serious aspects to the point of excluding entire categories of young people from the right to study because of the very high overall costs that families of origin have to bear - explains the head of Sunia's design office, Laura Mariani, - in these cities, the high demand from students has so distorted the market that a process of generalized increase has begun even for residents.
In most cases, rental offers also contain a series of violations: free-to-end, unregistered, no-rent contracts, sublettings.
For Sunia, extraordinary interventions through the revision of the tax are necessary to calm prices.
Reading in detail the survey, we see that in Milan, for a bed in the Brianza area, it takes about 450 euros; for a single room, we go from 650 euros minimum (Bande Nere area), to an average value of 800 (Lambiate zone, Udine, and Fiera) to a maximum of 900 euros (Vittoria zone)
In Florence, a bed costs on average, 350/400 euros, a room about 700 euros.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in areas close to the University, it takes 250/280 euros for a bed in a double, and 370 to 500 for a single room.
In Rome, in the areas close to the central universities (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna), we ask about 600 euros for a single, 450 for a bed in a double.
Slightly lower values (550 euro for a single) for areas close to other Universities (Ostiense and Cinecittà).
You can only save if you move away in peripheral areas: 300 euro for a bed, and 450 for a single in the Predestina, Centocelle or similar area.
In Naples, for a bed it takes 300/400 euros, for a single, you spend 400 to 600 euros, with higher prices in the areas Policlinico, Vomero, and Colli Aminei.
In Bari, for bed, it takes 250/350 euros, at least 350 for a single.
In smaller cities, prices are lower in absolute terms, but they are of major importance in the urban economy.
Finally, cities such as Perugia, in which rentals are often taken by non-EU students, there is a further anomaly: the rent charged to foreign students is increased by 25/30% compared to that applied to Italians.
Goodbye old Paradiso cinema, cities eliminate historic cinemas.
Historic movie theaters are closing in favor of Multiplexes.
"A city without movie theaters is a blind city, it's like a face without eyes"
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore, illustrates well what happens in the large Italian urban centers, but also in the provincial cities,
The process of marginalization of cinemas, with the birth on the outskirts of large multiscreens, and the death of consumption of single-screens in the central areas of cities, is one of the major events that seems inevitable and indisputable to us; It also has all the characteristics of a real cultural crime.
To disappear, they are often historical places and full of memory, "it's as if one of my friends disappeared, someone we know, with whom we shared a piece of the road and so many emotions" observes the director of the Nuovo cinema Paradiso, a film that offers Tornatore 20 years ago, the first Oscar as well as the Grand Prix de la jurée de Cannes,  and which told the poetry of a provincial theater, and the nostalgia of a way of living the cinema, lost perhaps forever.
The figures provided by Anec, the main association of traders, say it all: in the last five years, 316 traditional cinemas have closed, and it is the cinemas of the main cities that have mainly paid the costs: 10 less in Florence, 9 in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 fewer in Turin, 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closure, Roman Emilia is in the lead with 82 single-screen cinemas lost, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
The proof that confirms that the main cause of their disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, because it is the three Italian regions that have recorded the most new multi-screen cinemas: 195 more screens in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
"Italian exploitation has developed irrationally," observes Paolo Protti, president of Anec, "it is useful to build new structures, but we should still guarantee the survival of those that already exist, because when a theater closes in a city, these frequents are not necessarily all willing to go to multiplexes.
Not to mention the failed deliberation of credit in favor of traders: the antecedent debt of the State is about 10 million euros.
It is shameful that, from an ethical and moral point of view, the Government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector, between €16 million and €18 million per year would be needed.
Note the case of Bologna, the first Italian city that, concerned about these closures, decided to resolve the situation through the signing of a protocol between City Council and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy, to defend and promote single-screen cinemas in historic centers and on the outskirts.
Among the planned regulations, there are tax relief measures for managers and advantages for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic zone, and will have special rates for parking and in certain car parks.
"This is an initiative that I like," observes Giuseppe Tornatore, "and I hope that other cities will follow the example of Bologna by implementing other measures.
However, it is clear that, in order to contrast the superpower of multiplexes, traditional cinemas must also improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a theme that for me has always been important: the closure of the Supercinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to make "New Cinema Paradiso" that I had already been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass the Rialto, or the Quirinal of Via Nazionale, now closed, where I have experienced so many shared emotions, I turn to the other side so as not to see the panels blackened by dust.
