When the energy is born from the waves, now the big ones are launched.
This is an inordinate deposit that occupies more than 70% of the planet's surface and now the world's major energy companies are discovering it.
Waves, currents, tides, these are the new renewable sources on which giants like Chevron have laid their eyes, and now are trying to get their hands on them.
The possibility of obtaining energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for a hundred years now, and in the 70s, in conjunction with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil fell, around 1980, the idea of exploiting marine energy was shelved, but now the environmental authorities and the new increase in oil give a great boost to the sector.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London estimated in 2007 that 15% of the world's electricity needs could be met by sea swell systems.
This amount would be double that produced by nuclear power plants.
And in addition, there would be currents and tides.
Colossi on the attack.
The first company to bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 signed an agreement to build a plant in northern Portugal.
When the agreement was announced, it looked like a real revolutionary step.
Two years away, more and more candidates among these companies that have always been dedicated to traditional energy are betting on marine energy.
"Chevron is currently studying ocean energy technologies," a spokesman for a company associated with the U.S. oil giant told the Wall Street Journal business daily, "and is evaluating opportunities to cooperate with us."
The cooperation in question concerns the obtaining of a deliberate permit by the United States Energy Commission, necessary to give rise to a project to exploit marine energy in Alaska.
This is a very interesting signal, especially considering that precisely in Alaska, the US continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush has set up a project for new excavations.
